<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Trilateral Talks: Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said Wednesday that progress was made in his
talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and United States
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told a news conference that progress was made in
three areas: opening an industrial park in the Gaza Strip with
Israel's security concerns addressed, forming a committee
monitoring what he said the Palestinians' anti-Israel incitement
in education and media and activating person-to-person program
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
His remarks echoed Albright's comments on the trilateral talks
that "significant and substantial progress" has been made on
various issues about the Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu denied any U.S. pressure on him to yield tangible
results in the talks with the Palestinians, saying that the
progress was made out of willingness.
</P>
<P>
Despite the progress, Netanyahu said there are issues
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
"We are going up the mountain, but we still have the mountain
to face." 
</P>
</TEXT>
