<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Secure Trade Contract With Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's army has secured a 50
million U.S. dollar contract to supply various products to the
war-torn Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the state-owned
Herald newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean newspaper said an army subsidiary, the Zimbabwe
Defense Industries, has set up a venture under which the DRC
government will pay spot prices for all the goods supplied by the
Zimbabwen army.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean companies have been initially offered 10 million
dollars of the contract to supply items such as maize meal, rice,
vegetables, pharmaceuticals and agricultural, mining and other
equipment, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government deployed about 3,000 troops and a
number of war planes and tanks in the DRC to help President
Laurent Kabila fend off rebel forces after the rebles rose up
against the Kabila regime on August 2, this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
