<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Army Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Army Chief and
Chairman of the Joint Chiefs Staff Committee General Jahangir
Karamat resigned from his office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by Pakistan Television (PTV) Wednesday
night, Karamat sent a letter to Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif,
requesting him to accept his retirement. Karamat's tenure of
office is due in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif has accepted Karamat's resignation and
has appointed Lt. General Pervez Musharaf as the new army chief.
</P>
<P>
Karamat said in his letter that he had proposed the
establishment of the National Security Council. However,
unnecessary debate has started on the issue, so he decided to
step down so that a healthy tradition is set for future.
</P>
<P>
Karamat said at the Pakistan Navy War College in Lahore Monday
that in the present geo-strategic environment "our internal
security was the most significant facet of national security."
</P>
<P>
A national security council or committee at the apex would
institutionalize decision making if "it was backed by a team of
credible advisors and a think tank of experts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Karamat said that unlike countries with economic potential,
Pakistan could not afford the effects of polarization, vendettas
and insecurity driven expedient policies.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that as he had repeatedly stressed the need of
the hour was total focus on the economy, the external linkages
with China, Iran, Afghanistan, India, the U.S., the internal
situation, especially Sindh province, the sectarian aspect and
finally the fears of the smaller provinces.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the political mandate needed to be translated
into institutional strength, "otherwise we would have a permanent
election campaign environment in the country."
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have backed Karamat's proposal of
establishing a national security council and described his
strongly- worded statement as "the final warning" to the
government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif which came to power in
February 1997.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time for Karamat, who became army chief
nearly three years ago, to suggest direct army involvement in
policy decisions through a national security council.
</P>
<P>
However, the government, dogged by economic turmoil and bitter
opposition to a proposed constitutional amendment that would
create a new Islamic order in the country, has made no official
comment on Karamat's proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
