<HEADLINE> Zambians Getting Poorer, Says UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has slipped from 136 in
1996 to 146 in 1998 in a descending order of development listed
by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The per capita GDP in Zambia has fallen gradually from 463
U.S. Dollars in 1974 to 257 Dollars in 1995, according to a
report obtained Wednesday from the office of UNDP's resident
representative in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The publication entitled "Human Development Report 1998" shows
the per capita income of Zambia also fell from 440 Dollars in
1970 to 257 Dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the report does not include statistics in 1997 when
Zambia registered a 5.5 percent growth of its GDP.
</P>
<P>
The report also says that of the 9.6 million Zambians, 70
percent are living below the poverty line and their daily per
capita supply of calories reduced from 2,140 in 1970 to 1,915 in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The downtrend in Zambia's economic performance in recent years
was mainly attributed to the country's slow privatization
progress, heavy foreign debt which is currently estimated at 7.1
billion Dollars and reduction of cereal production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenstock: Council Is United On Comprehensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council was United on the question of conducting a
comprehensive review of Iraq's progress in dismantling its weapons
of mass destruction, Council President Jeremy Greenstock said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Greenstock, Britain's Ambassador to the United Nations, said
all the members of the Security Council had agreed that the
comprehensive review should be conducted in accordance with U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"That is the United Nations Special Commission in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction has got its work
to do and Iraq has offered the full disclosure (of its weapons
programme) and cooperation," Greenstock said.
</P>
<P>
Greenstock was responding to the remarks of Iraq's Deputy Prime
Minister Aziz. Aziz said Tuesday that he had not got sufficient
guarantees from the Council that it would conduct a comprehensive
review of Iraq's compliance with the relevant resolutions of the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The President said Iraq could not afford this time to miss the
opportunity and Iraq must move forward if it wished to get the
comprehensive review.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Regions in Somalia Face Famine Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Somali Democratic
Movement (SDM) faction of Bay and Bakol regions in southern
Somalia issued a statement Wednesday expressing concern over
serious drought that has hit the regions.
</P>
<P>
Two children under five and an elderly woman have died of
hunger in the remote village of Dhanawe, 90 km northeast of
Huddor, since the beginning of the month, according to Ali
Mohamed Ibrahim, the SDM health affairs secretary.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim said ten villages in the region of Bakol are the worst
famine-hit areas where more than 3,000 people are now at risk of
dying of hunger. Marasmus and skeleton-like children could be
seen everywhere.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people have already fled their villages to the
Sheikh Aweys shrine at Biyoley village, 75 km northeast of
Huddor, to pray for rain, while many others sought sanctuary
against the hunger in the shrine. Thousands of Somalis believe
in going to the Sheikh Aweys shrine annually as part of the
religion.
</P>
<P>
People from the area said the drought was mainly caused by
last year's disastrous floods and the subsequent failed attempt
in farming in the past season.
</P>
<P>
"The land has almost become barren after the crops were washed
away last year," said Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said the situation is further aggravated by
sporadic armed clashes between Hussein Aidid's men in the region
and those of the Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA).
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim said malnutrition-related diseases such as
tuberculosis, diarrhoea and malaria are also tightening their
grip on the people in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Skin diseases are also very common," said Ibrahim who
appealed to the international community and regional
organizations to help the people of Bakol region before the
situation deteriorated to the 1991 level.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, there are no humanitarian non-governmental
organizations operating in Bakol region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, despite security problems, the World Food Program
(WFP) is trying hard to get food for the people in the remote
regions and provinces in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
WFP managed to get 400 tons of food to Bakol two months ago.
However, it was barely enough for one village, said Ibrahim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
