<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Belgrade Has to Comply Fully With U.N. Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday warned Belgrade that the only way to avoid air strikes
by the West would be full compliance with U.N. demands to end the
violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters during a photo opportunity with Hungarian
Prime Minister Viktor Obran, Clinton also acknowledged that the
ultimate solution for the situation in Kosovo most likely would
require an allied military presence on the ground.
</P>
<P>
"The way to avoid NATO military action" is for Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to honor the U.N. resolutions
demanding a halt in Serb military action in Kosovo, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it is absolutely imperative that there be a
ceasefire, a withdrawal of troops, that the humanitarian groups
get access to these hundreds of thousands of people who have been
displaced, and that negotiations resume," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to efforts by Russia to find a diplomatic solution to
the situation, Clinton told reporters "the most important thing we
can do is work with the Russians to try to actually avoid military
strikes by securing compliance."
</P>
<P>
Russia has voiced its strong opposition to any military action
by NATO in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
"If he (Milosevic) does that, if he completely complies, he
doesn't have to worry about military force," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton acknowledged that even in the best case scenario, it
was likely that an outside force would be required.
</P>
<P>
"If there are negotiations which result in a settlement, there
might be some request for an international presence to help the
parties to honor a peace agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the makeup of such a force would have to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen on Tuesday said that the U.S.
would supply the preponderance of air power for any NATO strikes
and that any ground operation should be the responsibility of
European nations.
</P>
<P>
Many members of Congress oppose sending U.S. ground troops to
Kosovo because the use of thousands of American and other
peacekeeping troops in Bosnia has continued for more than two
years with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
NATO has threatened to launch air strikes against Yugoslavia
unless Belgrade authorities end the conflict with Kosovo Albanian
separatists and negotiates an autonomy agreement with them for the
southern Serbian province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
