<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspectors Demand Full Disclosure by Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. arms inspectors said
on Wednesday that Iraq's disarmament is possibly near its end in
the missile and chemical weapons areas but not in the biological
weapons area.
</P>
<P>
"Full disclosure by Iraq of all necessary material and
information remains the crucial ingredient for both an end to the
disarmament process and future monitoring," said Richard Butler,
Executive Chairman of UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM stands for the U.N. Special Commission in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, including
biological, chemical and nuclear weapons and the long-range
missiles used to deliver them before the Security Council will
lift sanctions imposed after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report to the Security Council on inspection
activities in the last six months, Butler said Iraq is permitting
UNSCOM's monitoring work to be exercised "only at a less than
satisfactory level".
</P>
<P>
The report said a satisfactory resolution of the question of the
chemical warfare agent VX needs to be achieved, because of its
implications for both the Chemical weapons and missile files.
</P>
<P>
Butler said there are "additional very serious impediments to
the Commission (UNSCOM)'s disarmament work caused by Iraq's
unilateral destruction and concealment actions and its
withholding of relevant documents."
</P>
<P>
"The effects of these actions by Iraq may prove to be that the
Commission is obliged to conclude that it is unable to provide 100
percent verification of the claimed fate or disposition of
prohibited weapons," the report said.
</P>
<P>
When such a conclusion comes to be accepted by the Security
Council, the effectiveness of the future monitoring system,
including UNSCOM's right of full access to any relevant sites,
"becomes even more important," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report came amid a standoff between Iraq and UNSCOM on arms
inspections. On August 5, Iraq decided to suspend cooperation with
UNSCOM, citing "the American influence" on UNSCOM's activities.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has urged Iraq to fully comply with
relevant U.N. resolutions and there have been consultations on how
to implement U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's proposal for a
comprehensive review of U.N. inspections in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
