<HEADLINE> Kenya Shilling Strengthens Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Shilling firmed
slightly against the U.S. Dollar Wednesday, breaking
the-60-to-the-Dollar barrier amid heavy mid-morning Dollar sales.
</P>
<P>
Dealers quoted the Shilling at around 59.85/59.95 at 09:30 GMT
Wednesday, from around 59.90/60.00 at the opening.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it will hold (at less than 60 Shillings to one
Dollar) for very long," said one dealer, though others said weak
demand for the Dollar could strengthen the Shilling further.
</P>
<P>
"We're seeing heavy selling (of Dollars) from exporters," said
one dealer.
</P>
<P>
Exporter selling the Dollar has dominated the Kenyan currency
market all year, while import demand for Dollars remains low.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the Shilling was boosted by sentiment that the
national teachers' strike, which began Monday, was not having a
significant impact on Kenya's political and social stability.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya quoted a mean commercial rate of
59.9528 to the Dollar at Wednesday's opening, from Tuesday's
59.9811. 
</P>
</TEXT>
