<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Parliament Criticizes SADC Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Southern African
Development Community (SADC) proposals on the establishment of a
transitional structure until new elections are held in Lesotho
were criticized by Lesotho parliament members Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the first sitting of the National Assembly since it was
adjourned on September 14, parliament member Pashu Mochesane said
the transitional committee suggested by the SADC to prepare for
the elections in 15 to 18 months was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
He said Lesotho could not set up a structure like South
Africa's transitional executive council set up before its first
democratic election in 1994, as the conditions in South Africa at
the time and in Lesotho at present were different, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the present Lesotho government was properly elected
and there was no need for a transitional structure.
</P>
<P>
It was inconceivable for the proposed transitional committee
to access confidential cabinet minutes, particularly in the
sensitive areas of foreign affairs, security and finance,
Mochesane said.
</P>
<P>
Another parliament member, Litsitso Sekamane, also criticized
the SADC proposal, saying there was no provision for such a
structure in the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
Sekamane called for action against the perpetrators of the
violence and looting in Lesotho two weeks ago, saying many of the
culprits were well known.
</P>
<P>
After the May election, the ruling Lesotho Congress for
Democracy (LCD) has 79 of the 80 seats in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
A SADC delegation to Monday's multi-party talks in Lesotho
presented the proposal as the LCD and opposition parties
disagreed on the formation of an interim coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties agreed to take the proposal to its
supporters, saying if their supporters agree to it, they would
also agree. Government also said it was in favor of the proposal
in principle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
