<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Hails Progress, 'New Spirit' in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EREZ BORDER CROSSING, October 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said Wednesday substantial progress had
been made in an extended trilateral meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference after more than four hours of talks at
the border crossing between Israel and the Gaza Strip, Albright
said the extended meeting was "important and very productive."
</P>
<P>
She said that she found in the meeting a "new spirit," a
spirit of cooperation and a strong sense of urgency, on both
sides. She described the spirit as "quite helpful" and wished it
will be carried onto the Washington summit, which she announced
will be held on October 15 between Netanyahu, Arafat and
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Significant and substantial progress" has been made in the
meeting on various issues including the further Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank, the security cooperation, the opening of the
Gaza airport and industrial park.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians also agreed to form a joint
committee monitoring anti-Israel incitement in Palestinian
education system and media, and to activate a people-to-people
program.
</P>
<P>
Albright is on the second day of her shuttle diplomacy aimed at
paving the way for the scheduled Washington summit, or in her
words, to put in place the building blocks for the summit.
</P>
<P>
As far as her goal is concerned, Albright said she was "more
than satisfied" with the meeting.
</P>
<P>
She said the "new spirit" was evident in the meeting, noting
that Netanyahu crossed the border into the Palestinian-control
area for the first time for a working lunch with her and
Arafat. Albright toasted at the lunch to "a new chapter" of the
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
What also characterized the "new spirit" was the handshake
between Netanyahu and Arafat before the meeting, a significant
move since the two did not manage to do so when they met twice in
Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
Later at a news conference held in Jerusalem, Netanyahu echoed
Albright by saying that progress has been made. He denied that he
made the move under U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
If an agreement on the second Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank is signed at the Washington summit, there is a possibility
that the two sides will enter the final-status talks on the spot,
Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Although Albright said the progress will enable Israel and the
Palestinians to be in "a far better position" to finalize all the
issues at the Washington summit, both she and Netanyahu stressed
that there were still a lot of problems remained to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Albright warned against overoptimism, saying she is
"realistic," while the Israeli prime minister said: "We are going
up the slope, but there is still the mountain to face."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state will leave the region for Europe
later Wednesday, but U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross and
Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk will continue the
efforts "to move the ball on." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
