<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy to Shuttle Between Cypriot Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. envoy said here Wednesday
that she will soon start separate talks with leaders of Cyprus'
two communities after "productive" and "useful" visits to Athens
and Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Upon returning from her trips to Greece and Turkey, Dame Ann
Hercus, the United Nations chief Kofi Annan's deputy special
representative for Cyprus, said that "both visits were very
productive."
</P>
<P>
"In both capitals I had very useful discussions which provide a
positive perspective for my efforts," Hercus said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy has paid "an introductory visit" to Greece and
Turkey, where she held talks with the two countries' foreign
ministers and other officials on the protracted Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Hercus said the positive results of her visits will facilitate
her shuttle mission between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has decided that Hercus starts contacts with the two
Cypriot communities aimed at reducing tensions and promoting
progress toward a just and lasting settlement.
</P>
<P>
Both Clerides and Denktash have "expressed their support for
such a process and have promised to cooperate in a constructive
and flexible manner," a U.N. statement issued last week said.
</P>
<P>
The direct talks between the two sides broke down last year
after Denktash walked out of the talks in protest against European
Union's decision to start accession negotiations with the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after an
abortive coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying ever since to help reunify the island
under a bizonal and bicommunal formula. But so far no tangible
results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
