<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Satisfied with Result of Protest Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
was satisfied that the protest actions held by a number of
political forces throughout the country proceeded calmly,
presidential press secretary Dmitri Yakushkin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin said that the president closely followed the protests
and contacted security and police chiefs, who reported the
situation in various regions.
</P>
<P>
According to the presidential spokesman, Yeltsin expressed
"cautious hope" that the nation is retreating from headlong
confrontation and said "the nation has matured".
</P>
<P>
A long-designed nationwide protest action organized by the
Federation of Free Russian Trade Union and the Communist Party of
Russia was held Wednesday in Moscow, St.Petersburg and 493 other
towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 rallied in Moscow outside the Kremlin, while a
total of 615,000 people participated in the protest actions
throughout Russia, Yakushkin quoted the presidential side as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The protester mainly demanded the resignation of the president
and payment of wage arrears, as well as adoption of laws to
guarantee the social rights of the working people.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Russia's Independent Trade Unions Mikhail Shmakov
said that if the president cannot cope with the social problems,
he should leave the post of president immediately.
</P>
<P>
Shmakov also announced that the trade unions were ready to back
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's economic program, giving the top
priority to the development of the national industry.
</P>
<P>
Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov on the whole agreed
with the new government's initial steps and Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov's address on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He believed the government's initial steps aimed at working out
a more realistic policy have yielded positive results.
</P>
<P>
The police took some 25 young protesters from the area around
St. Basil's Cathedral near the red square to the police department
at 19:00 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's nationwide protest actions were the seventh since
the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
