<HEADLINE> Iraqi Kurdish Leader Condemns Fresh Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Leader of Iraq's Kurdistan
Democratic Party has vehemently condemned the fresh Turkish
intervention in the autonomous Kurdish region in northern Iraq,
official Iraqi News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the agency, the party's
Secretary-General Ahmad Mohammed al-Atroushi held Turkey
responsible for the results of its "irresponsible behaviors and
its interferences" in Iraq's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi Foreign Ministry spokesman said on Monday that on
October 2, over 10,000 Turkish troops launched a new invasion
against Iraq under the pretext of tracking down rebellious
elements threatening Turkish national security.
</P>
<P>
Al-Atroushi said in his statement that it is not in the
interest of Turkey to launch an aggression on Iraq but rather to
enhance cooperation and good relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey's failure to settle its internal problems and to grant
Kurdish and other nationalities their national rights will
aggravate Turkey's problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
The outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party has been fighting since
1984 for autonomy in southeast Turkey. It frequently launched
cross-border attacks on Turkish government troops from their bases
in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish incursions into northern Iraq is in line with the
U.S. strategy. It is a chapter of vicious aggression on the people
of Iraq," al-Atroushi said.
</P>
<P>
His remarks echoed that of Iraqi Foreign Ministry spokesman who
said that the fresh Turkish invasion coincided with the feverish
activities made by the U.S. with the objective of placing the
region under its hegemony.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long been accusing Turkey of making its territory as
a spring board for the U.S. and British forces to impose the
no-fly zone in northern Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
