<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Risks Loss of GA Vote Next Year With No Due Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- United Nations member
states owe the world body 2.507 billion U.S. dollars, and the
United States, which remains the largest contributor to the U.N.
financial crisis, will risk "automatic loss" of its vote in the
General Assembly in the coming year, a senior U.N. official said
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Connor, U.N. under-secretary-general for management,
told a press conference that the United States owed the United
Nations some 1.6 billion U.S. dollars in arrears, which accounts
for 67 percent of the total unpaid dues.
</P>
<P>
"The loss of vote in the General Assembly (GA) under Article
19 (of the U.N. Charter) is automatic unless the GA specificly
decides to grant an exception or until the minimum necessary
payment has been received," he said.
</P>
<P>
In late November and early December, the U.N. Secretariat
alerts those member states, including the United States, that they
are in danger in the following year of application of Article 19
of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat usually sends a letter to a Member Country who
does not pay its back dues, informing it of how much it owes and
the amount of the minimum payable in order to avoid the
application of Article 19.
</P>
<P>
The article says: "A Member State of the United Nations which
is in arrears in the payment of its financial contributions to the
Organization shall have no vote in the General Assembly if the
amount of its arrears equals or exceeds the amount of the
contributions due from it for the preceding two full years."
</P>
<P>
The two-year period ran from the beginning of December 1996
to the end of November 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
If the United States does not pay its back dues, it will
"surely" lose its vote in the General Assembly in 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
The non-payment of dues had caused a regular budget deficit
which could grow as high as 247 million U.S. dollars by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, cash in the peacekeeping budget was expected to be
around 775 million U.S. dollars at the end of this year -- the
lowest amount in five years -- and a significant portion of it
would be cross-borrowed to "bail out" the regular budget.
</P>
<P>
As a result of cross-borrowing from the peacekeeping budget,
there would be little -- if any -- funds left to pay the more
than 860 million U.S. dollars owed to Member States for troops
and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2.507 billion U.S. dollars owed to the United Nations as
of the end of September, 67 percent was due from the United States,
and Washington also owed some 61 percent of the outstanding
peacekeeping dues, estimated at the end of September to be 1.701
billion U.S. dollars, Connor said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not through a new financial crisis (within the U.N.
system), but we are through the replay of the 1995 financial
crisis," he said, referring to the year with lowest amount of
the payment of regular budget assessments.
</P>
<P>
On the positive side, Connor said that for the first time in
recent years, more than 100 Member States had paid their regular
budget contributions in full for 1998 and all prior years by the
end of September.
</P>
<P>
Although this was heartening, the overall picture was not:
some 81 percent of the 1998 assessments had been received, down
from 88 percent and 87 percent respectively in 1997 and 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Rapped for alleged Involvement in Congo (K) Crisis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and Rwandan Vice-President, Major General Paul Kagame,
war on the side of President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"Uganda and Rwanda strongly condemn the involvement of Sudan
in the conflict of the Democratic Republic of Congo and question
the wisdom of any continued support for the Kabila-Sudan
alliance," the two leaders said in a joint communique issued in
Rwakitura, Uganda Tuesday, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
But Sudan denied any involvement in the Congo Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kagame had gone to Rwakitura, Museveni's farm, on Monday to
discuss with him the on-going crisis in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The statement issued at the end of the meeting commended
efforts being made in search of a solution to the crisis in Congo
(K) where Tutsi-led rebels revolted since August 2 and now still
occupy large tracts of territory in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
Uganda also reiterated the purpose of its presence in Congo,
saying, "the military presence of Uganda in the Democratic
Republic of Congo is based on genuine and legitimate security

interests and on its determination to prevent genocide."
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda continues to face insecurity caused by former Rwanda
armed forces (ex-Far)" and "Interahamwe militia based in the
Democratic Republic of Congo and supported by the Kabila
government," RNA quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda also Charged the Kabila regime with carrying out the
state-inspired acts of genocide and ethnic cleansing of targeted
groups of people in Democratic Congo.
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda reiterated its resolve to deal with the above concerns
using all appropriate means," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia sent troops to stop the rebels'
marching on capital Kinshasa and drive them out of the west in
late August, and Chad also sent troops to help Kabila fight the
rebels in the east.
</P>
<P>
At the end of their meeting the two leaders called for a
negotiated settlement of the conflict through talks that would
involve the government in Kinshasa, the Congolese rebels, and
opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
So far Kabila refuses to have direct talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
All the resolution of the Congo crisis must "address in an
acceptable and sustainable way, the legitimate interests of all
the neighboring states," the two leaders said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
