<HEADLINE> Conf Seeks Peaceful Solutions to Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The first Great Lakes Region
Conference ended here Wednesday with a communique demanding all
member states promote dialog with warring parties in Congo (K)
and devise lasting solutions to armed conflicts in the area.
</P>
<P>
The conference, themed as "Strategies for Conflict Management
and Peace Building," was organized by the Foundation for Human
Rights Initiative, Radio Uganda reported Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
As far as the Congo (K) conflict is concerned, the delegates
suggested that all foreign troops withdraw immediately and that
the Congolese government develop a constitutional framework for
democratic governance.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that the Ugandan government, the opposition and
all rebels in Uganda should engage in meaningful dialog for
peace.
</P>
<P>
On Rwanda, the communique resolved that the government should
intensify the process of Ethnic Reconciliation in order to
promote peace in the country which has suffered a lot from ethnic
strife.
</P>
<P>
Livingstone Sewanyana, the executive director of the
Foundation, condemned all kinds of aggression and armed violence,
the report added. 
</P>
