<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Signs Higher Education Assistance Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Wednesday signed a higher education bill, which lowers
student-loan interest rates that would save borrowers an estimated
11 billion U.S. dollars over five years.
</P>
<P>
"Today with this lowering of the interest rates... we can
really say that every high school graduate in America, regardless
of income, can afford to go to college," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The White House said a typical student borrower at a four-year
college, graduating with 13,000 dollars in debt, would save about
700 dollars over a 10-year repayment period.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, while appreciating both Democratic and Republican
lawmakers for their support to the bill, called on Congress to
approve other education bills, including his proposals for hiring
100,000 more public school teachers to reduce class sizes and
spending more to modernize aging school buildings.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the higher education bill would enhance the
economic strength, strengthen the communities, improve the lives
of families and widen the circle of opportunity in the nation.
</P>
<P>
The bill creates a new interest-rate formula for student loans.
The rate for students would be 7.46 percent for graduates starting
to repay their loans, the lowest rate in 17 years. Rates are
capped at 8.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
Students who refinance their loans could get lower interest
rates if they applied before January 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The measure also raises the maximum authorized amount for Pell
Grants from the present 3,000 dollars to 4,500 dollars a year in
1999-2000, and in steps to 5,800 dollars in 2003-2004. But
Congress would have to provide the money.
</P>
<P>
The bill also raises the ceiling on grants and work-student for
needy students and takes steps to improve teacher preparation,
monitor college costs, report campus crimes, monitor hate crimes
and discourage drug or alcohol abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Reiterates Position on U.N.-backed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government
reiterated Wednesday that it is ready to engage in a dialog with
the Turkish Cypriot side on the basis of a bizonal, bicommunal
federation as provided by the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus will not accept any discussion on suggestions to deal
with the Turkish Cypriot side-proposed Cyprus confederation,
government spokesman Christos Stylianides said following a cabinet
meeting, shortly before the "on-island contacts" between the two
Cypriot communities, to be conducted by Dame Ann Hercus, the
U.N. chief Kofi Annan's deputy special representative in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that "our position is clear and
specific. There is no doubt how the government and the political
leadership will react to should the Turkish Cypriot side put
forward proposals for confederation during shuttle diplomacy
talks."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, who walked out of the
peace negotiations with the Cypriot government last year, proposed
in August the establishment of a confederation of two equal states
in Cyprus as the basis for the resumption of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal was rejected by the Cypriot government and
the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
After recent separate meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Denktash in New York, U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan proposed to develop a process "for on-island contacts with
both parties, with the goal of reducing tensions and promoting
progress toward a just and lasting settlement."
</P>
<P>
Hercus is expected to sponsor the shuttle talks with the two
sides soon after her consultations in Ankara and Athens. The
agenda of the talks has not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Turkish Cypriot position that U.N.-sponsored
talks should be conducted on the basis of the proposal for a Cyprus
confederation, the spokesman said "once more the Turkish Cypriot
side is trying to revoke events and facts as these have been
shaped within the framework of the Security Council, the
U.N. Secretary-General and the joint statement of the foreign
ministers of the permanent members of the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify the divided
island through a bizonal, bicommunal federation formula, but so
far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
