<HEADLINE> Angolan Ruling Party to Amend Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan ruling party Mpla
has made known its revised draft constitution, which will among
others abolish the position of deputy ministers and allow the
president to execute the right as head of the government.
</P>
<P>
The revised draft constitution published in a fortnightly
magazine run by the ruling People's Liberation Movement of
Angola, has enlarged from 166 to 339 articles on the presidential
system, which will greatly expand the power of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Civil rights, the cardinal principles of the state are also
expanded in the revised constitution draft, with death penalty
kept in the new laws.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution plans to drop out the positions of deputy
ministers and adds articles on the rights and treatment for
retired parliament members and former presidents.
</P>
<P>
An anti-corruption institution was also proposed in the new
document.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution needs consultations with other parties.
But it will go to parliamentary session and most likely be
adopted, as the ruling party has 129 seats in the legislature
while other parties have only 24 seats, apart from the banned
National Union for Total Independence of Angolas (UNITA) which
has 70 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
