<HEADLINE> Arafat Briefs Mubarak on Three-Way Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
held talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak upon his arrival
here on Wednesday night on his meetings with Israeli and U.S.
leaders, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held at the Cairo International Conference
Center and attended by Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri,
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, Presidential Political Advisor Osama
el-Baz, as well as Secretary General of Palestine Liberation
Organization Executive Committee Mahmoud Abbas and Arafat's
advisor Nabil Abu Redina.
</P>
<P>
Arafat explained the outcome of U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's separate talks with him and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the past two days and the
tripartite meeting among them earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite encounter lasted for two hours at the Israeli
side of the Erez crossing point and continued on the Palestinian
side of Beit Hanoun checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
After her lengthy talks with Israeli and Palestinian leaders,
Albright announced that an October 15 summit would be held in
Washington to try to work out agreement on a West Bank withdrawal
accord.
</P>
<P>
She said they have made "significant progress," and are in a
far better position to finalize all the issues.
</P>
<P>
Albright flew to the region to narrow differences between the
two sides on a U.S. proposal on a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank in exchange for Palestinian crackdown on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in Israel on Monday night on her third visit
to the region since she took office in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for Near Eastern Affairs
Martin Indyk and U.S. Mideast peace coordinator Dennis Ross will
hold further talks in the region after Albright's departure.
</P>
<P>
Indyk will arrive here later Wednesday in his capacity as an
envoy of Albright to inform Egypt about the results of the
intensive talks held in the past two days and the U.S. efforts to
salvage the long-stalled peace march. 
</P>
