<HEADLINE> Improved Water Supply Urged in Zambian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Lusaka Mayor Fisho Mwale called
here Wednesday for an improved water supply for the people living
in squatter compounds of the capital city.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 5,000 people in the squatter compounds share a
single tap for their water supply and the situation needs to be
changed, Mwale said.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 percent of the population of the city are living in
such compounds, according to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
Mwale said that water is a matter of life and death and
therefore any efforts made toward the improvement of the delivery
system to the residents is commendable.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal when a managing director of a tobacco
company, Kennedy Mandevhani of the Rothmans of Pall Mall Company,
made a pledge to donate a bore-hole in any area of Lusaka facing
persistent water problems.
</P>
<P>
Mwale promised to work promptly to identify an area in Lusaka
for the bore-hole to be dug. 
</P>
