<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Greens Agree on Alliance for Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's chancellor-elect Gerhard
Schroeder's Social Democratic Party (SPD) and its potential
partners, the Greens, agreed Wednesday to launch an Alliance for
Jobs to tackle the country's top issue -- high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a second round of coalition negotiations between
the SPD and Greens, Schroeder said that the two parties had agreed
on the outlines of their future economic policy with the reduction
of unemployment through an Alliance for Jobs as the center piece.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance for Jobs, a key plank of SPD policy, is a forum
for trade unions, employers and the government to work together to
create jobs and training places.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said that the Alliance for Jobs would specify the
duties for all parties concerned with regard to job creation.
Measures envisaged include more part-time jobs, less overtime jobs
and more training places for young people and improving employment
opportunities for the less qualified.
</P>
<P>
During their negotiations Wednesday, the two sides also worked
out a concept for rebuilding the depressed eastern German economy
and agreed in principle to start a so-call ecological tax reform
to reduce non-wage labor costs through an increase in energy
prices.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides admitted that they had still to face tough
negotiations Thursday to seek a compromise on the details of the
tax reform.
</P>
<P>
The ecology-minded Greens want to raise the price of petrol to
five German marks (about three U.S. dollars) per liter over the
next 10 years. The SPD has said that it would accept an increase
of six pfennigs per liter.
</P>
<P>
The two parties also differed on issues such as NATO expansion,
the shutdown of nuclear power plants, and whether to impose speed
limits on the German highways.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, who defeated Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the country's
general elections on September 27, said Wednesday that he saw good
chances for the SPD and Greens to wind up their coalition talks by
October 19.
</P>
<P>
If a coalition accord could be worked out, the new German
parliament would formally elect Schroeder chancellor on October
27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
