<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAEA Finds No Evidence of Nuclear Weapons in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA) in charge of verifying Iraq's nuclear weapons
reaffirmed Wednesday that Iraq has not achieved its program goal
of producing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna-based agency said it has found no indication of Iraq
having retained a physical capability for the production of
weapon-useable nuclear material or having clandestinely obtained
such material.
</P>
<P>
IAEA Director-General Mohamed ElBaradel made the remarks in the
agency's latest report to the U.N. Security Council. The report
covers IAEA's verification in the last six months. Similar
assessment was made in the previous report in April.
</P>
<P>
But the agency "points out the limitations inherent in a
countrywide verification process and consequently its inability to
guarantee that all readily concealable items have been found," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's decision on August 5 to suspend cooperation with IAEA
has prevented IAEA from exercising "full and free access" to new
verification sites, said IAEA, adding that "the level of assurance
the IAEA can give that prohibited activities are not taking place
is significantly reduced."
</P>
<P>
Nuclear weapons are included in the category of the weapons of
mass destruction which Iraq must destroy in exchange for the
Security Council to lift sanctions imposed on it after its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
