<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The European Union (EU) has agreed to grant Lebanon a
loan of 45 million U.S. dollars to help upgrade its
administration, the Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Beshara Merhej, Lebanese state minister for administrative
reform, said after a meeting with EU representatives on Tuesday
that the loan would cover half of the sum needed in a government
plan to develop the administration technically and train the
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Merhej said that this is the biggest loan given by the
15-nation European organization to Lebanon in a bid to develop its
administration.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's Transport Ministry is considering reducing
the transport fees on goods heading for Jordan via the port of
Beirut to compete with Israel, the Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The average transport fee from Lebanon to Jordan is estimated at
85 dollars per tonne, 63 dollars more than that from Israel's
Mediterranean port of Haifa, due to much longer distance.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese ministry has tried before to cut the fees on
vehicles carrying goods to Jordan. But it still has a long way to
go, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Abu Dhabi has announced that it is trying to
attract foreign investments to the oil and gas sector.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi and Dubai last week set up a company for producing
petrochemicals with a capital of 4 billion dirhams (1.1 billion
dollars), inviting foreign firms and the private sector of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) to join in.
</P>
<P>
The UAE and other Gulf countries need an estimated investment
of 50 billion dollars in the next 10 years for expanding the
oil and gas sector and the petrochemical industries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Two Saudi foodstuff companies have announced a
merger plan, which will lead to the emergence of the largest
foodstuff group in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Monday by Saudi Prince Walid Bin Talal said
the merger agreement was reached last week between his Alaziziya
United Banda Company and the Safola Company.
</P>
<P>
The capital of the merged company stands at 1.3 billion Saudi
riyals (346 million dollars), the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
