<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Assist Zambia With $100m in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A country director of the U.S.
Agency for International Development (USAID) said Wednesday that
his organization will continue ot assist Zambia with the required
aid of 100 million U.S. Dollars for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Briefing cooperating partners here in Lusaka, Walter North
said the aid to Zambia might increase, depending on the country's
economic performance and its democratic governance, according to
Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
North added that if Zambia did well in these two fields it
would be rewarded for its performance.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made after the western donors had suspended
their aid to Zambia in the past months on the excuse that the
country made little progress in privatization and good
governance.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement concluded with the Zambian government last
May, the donors would release 530 million Dollars to Zambia in
1998 on condition that the country could privatize its copper
mining conglomerate, the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
However, North was saddened to note that Zambia's legacy from
a generation of misrule was widespread poverty, an unsustainable
debt burden and crumbling infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 percent of the Zambians are living below the poverty
line and the country's foreign debt has amounted to 7.1 billion
Dollars in the past year, said a recently released report
prepared by the U.N. Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
USAID, which is a U.S. government agency responsible for
development assistance and has about 80 missions all over the
world, supports Zambia in four key areas of increasing rural
incomes, basic education, health and democratic governance.
</P>
</TEXT>
