<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End Volatile Session Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- It was a day of fluctuating
fortunes on the European stock markets, with shares eventually
ending lower.
</P>
<P>
The London Stock Exchange ended the day with modest losses,
with the FTSE 100 index of leading shares falling 25.1 to 4,828.9,
as financial stocks continued to recover ahead of Thursday's
interest rate verdict, which remains "too close to call."
</P>
<P>
The broader indices also pushed into negative territory. Market
volume stood at a healthy 995m shares.
</P>
<P>
"It's been another choppy day, but this time backed up by
decent volume," one broker from a U.K. bank said, adding that some
players had been "caught short" when the FTSE 100 bounced off its
intra-day low of 4,777.1 mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The balance of risks favors a 25 basis point cut tomorrow, but
only just," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee will announce
its decision on interest rates at midday. A quarter point cut had
been widely expected until the Office for National Statistics
revised up June average earnings growth Tuesday, which sparked
fears that domestically-generated inflation is not yet under
control.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the late session turnaround was largely fueled by
a surprising rally on Wall Street, where comments by U.S. Fed
chief Alan Greenspan raised hopes of another U.S. rate cut.
</P>
<P>
However, profit-taking quickly ate into the U.S. rally, which
in turn drove London lower as well.
</P>
<P>
Fresh hopes that Japan may at last address its banking problems
and the domestic rate outlook boosted financial stocks.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares resumed their downward slide on
after a one-day respite. The Xetra Dax closed down 121.2 points at
4,064.
</P>
<P>
A weak dollar against the Deutschmark, which could hit German
exports, and persistent concern over the effect the global
financial crisis will have on corporate profits lead to the
decline.
</P>
<P>
The index opened the day much higher on the back of strong
gains in Tokyo. But traders said volumes were thin. "This is the
end of the bounce," one trader said.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks also closed down, with the Cac 40 index
closing 38.8 points lower at 3,097.69. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
