<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slightly Higher Cancer Risk for Passive Smokers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A 10-year and large-scale
study across Europe indicates that adults exposed to second-hand
smoke at home and in the workplace have a slightly higher risk of
lung cancer, but it found no increased risk to children of passive
smoking.
</P>
<P>
The study, according to Wednesday's Washington Post, found
that passive smoking is a definite, although small, cause of lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Previous studies also shown that secondhand smoke can cause
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Researchers, led by Paolo Boffetta from International Agency
for Research on Cancer, said passive smokers breathed in about the
same amount of smoke as very light smokers who smoke a cigarette
every other day or so. They found that passive smokers have about
1 percent of cotinine, a breakdown product of nicotine, found in
the blood of active smokers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt Pledges to Safeguard Farmers' Inputs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian vice-president Christon
Tembo warned Wednesday the government will take stern measures to
punish anyone exporting illegally agricultural inputs intended
for local peasant farmers during this year's farming season.
</P>
<P>
He said in Eastern Province that the government has taken over
the responsibility of distributing the agricultural inputs to the
peasant farmers and will not condone the illegal export of
fertilizers and seed maize to neighboring countries by some
unscrupulous people at the expense of the farmers.
</P>
<P>
He told a public meeting that some agriculture credit
coordinators have over the past years intentionally dented the
government's image in the farmers' minds by hijacking and
illegally exporting fertilizers for their personal gains.
</P>
<P>
"I am appealing to all district agricultural officers and
village head men through whom the inputs will be disbursed to
report to the police anyone who will be seen and found to be
selling the fertilizers illegally for their selfish gains to
deprive the beneficiaries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the fertilizers have begun arriving in the country and
will sold at 30,000 (about 15 U.S. Dollars) for each 50kg bag and
peasant farmers who cannot afford to buy it will be given loans
on condition that they repay the loans with one 90kg bag of maize
for each fertilizer bag they obtained.
</P>
<P>
Tembo urged the farmers in the province and the country at
large to take advantage of the gesture because the government
will not continue to give the food relief hand-outs every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
