<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Vote on Principle, Not Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- With a vote to start an
impeachment inquiry against U.S. President Bill Clinton scheduled
for Thursday, the president Wednesday urged lawmakers to vote
their consciences while working the phones to build support in the
House of Representatives, where Republicans are expected to
approve impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a group of 40 freshman Democrats attended a White
House meeting with first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who also
urged them to vote based on "what they think is right," according
to White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first presidential impeachment proceeding since
Richard Nixon's Watergate scandal in 1974.
</P>
<P>
"I think everyone should cast a vote on principle and
conscience," Clinton told reporters during a photo session with
visiting Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orban.
</P>
<P>
"It's up to others to decide what happens to me, and ultimately
it's going to be up to the American people to make a clear
statement there," he said.
</P>
<P>
The White House invited the freshman Democrats for a session
with the first lady, who urged them to vote for a Democratic
alternative that would limit the length and scope of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
She told them to base their vote on "what they think is right,
what their conscience tells them to vote," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said, "She made the explicit point that this White
House stands ready to work with Democrats, support Democrats, help
them get elected, work into the future, no matter how they vote."
</P>
<P>
Democratic House members, uncertain how the vote might affect
the November 3 mid-term elections, met in closed caucus Wednesday
morning to discuss the upcoming vote.
</P>
<P>
Participants said the meeting was tense at times as a divided
caucus tried to plot a course through an impeachment process that
could spell trouble for Democrats in close races, news reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton played down the perception that he was engaged in an
aggressive lobbying campaign trying to talk Democrats into not
joining with Republicans to approve the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
"There have been conversations with members," he said. "A large
number called me, and I am attempting to call them all back."
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich also called Thursday's decision
"vote of conscience."
</P>
<P>
"There will be no whipping of our members, there will be no
arm-twisting. Members need to take this vote as a matter of
conscience and we'll let the chips fall where they may tomorrow,"
he said after a Republican caucus Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On a party-line 21-16 vote, the House Judiciary Committee late
Monday approved launching the inquiry and rejected two Democratic
alternatives that would have limited the length and scope of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Democrats struggled to hash out another alternative plan, which
would be offered as part of a procedural vote Thursday to send the
resolution back to committee, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
