<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Seek Parliamentary Consent for War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz said here Wednesday that his government might request
parliamentary consent for a war with Syria, although war is still
not desired.
</P>
<P>
Addressing deputies in the parliament following a cabinet
meeting to determine Turkey's policy towards Syria, Yilmaz said
that "we are not trying to create a war with Syria. The real
objective is to safeguard Turkey's vital interests."
</P>
<P>
"We don't really wish to do so, but if necessary, we are ready
to get the consent of the parliament," he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister pointed out that Syria has been supporting
the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) for 14 years, but has
denied it.
</P>
<P>
He said that "I would like to reiterate that Turkey has been
given the right for self-defense according to Article 51 of the
United Nations Charter."
</P>
<P>
Ankara has given Damascus a viable opportunity through
diplomatic channels with good intentions, but the Syrian
administration had not responded to these calls, said Yilmaz,
adding that "Syria believes that it can get away by denying the
realities."
</P>
<P>
He added that Syria has been irresponsibly denying that it is
sheltering PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan, who controls his illegal
organization and contacts foreign government officials.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has demanded that Syria extradite Ocalan, stop PKK
attacks on Turkey from the Syrian territory, punish the attackers
and give up supporting the PKK with weapons, money and logistics,
said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Turkey will not allow Syria to use its
support for international terrorism as a bargaining
chip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
