<HEADLINE> Kenyan Stock Market in Record Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nairobi stock market, which
saw a sustained downturn lately, has hit a record low in 10
years, caused by recent economic and political chaos, trend
analysts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts warned that if the government carries out the
controversial teachers' 150-200 percent pay rise promised last
year, its domestic debt may rise through Treasury bills,
diverting investors from the equity market to the money market.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide teachers' strike demanding the government's
implementation of the pay rise has entered the third day
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A stock-broker said the strike had made investors fear that
implementing the new salary structure may plunge the country into
serious depression as the economic growth is already slowing
down.
</P>
<P>
"If the government has to pay teachers, the 1.2 billion
Shillings (20 million U.S. Dollars) may have to be raised through
domestic debt, forcing interest rates up," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This will in turn attract more investors to the Treasury
bills and bonds markets, instead of the equity market," said the
stock-broker.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the stock market had already suffered a blow,
following the recent collapse of several small banks in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Anxiety on the planned Vote of no-confidence by some
opposition lawmakers against the government had also put on hold
some prospective investors.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, there was improved trading at the stock market,
as turnover went up to 7.1 million Shillings, from Tuesday's 3.93
million Shillings.
</P>
<P>
A Nairobi Stock Exchange official said later that plans were
underway to start recruiting new companies, to increase liquidity
in the market.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the market trend is not good, with many trading
companies, at least we will be assured of more liquidity than it
is at the moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 146,000 shares changed hands in 240 deals
Wednesday, compared to 104,000 shares in 163 deals previously.
</P>
</TEXT>
