<HEADLINE> Israeli Jewish Settlement Conferred City Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Despite United States call to
halt settlement construction, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu conferred city status Wednesday to the Ariel Jewish
settlement in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony, Netanyahu told settlers that Ariel
would remain under the sovereignty of Israel.
</P>
<P>
"This place will be part of Israel in any final status
agreement in the future," he said
</P>
<P>
He said the local authority would build a new cultural center
in Ariel and the community college would be expanded into a
university.
</P>
<P>
The settlement, established in 1977, is located in the middle
of the West Bank, about 30 kilometers east of the Israeli coastal
city of Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held hours after U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright wrapped up a mediation mission between Israel
and the Palestinians over the overdue Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Both the Palestinians and the U.S. oppose Israel's settlement
activities in the occupied territories, calling on the Jewish
state to halt unilateral actions. 
</P>
