<HEADLINE> Sudan Rapped for alleged Involvement in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and Rwandan Vice-President, Major General Paul Kagame,
have condemned the alleged involvement of Sudan in the Congo (k)
war on the side of President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"Uganda and Rwanda strongly condemn the involvement of Sudan
in the conflict of the Democratic Republic of Congo and question
the wisdom of any continued support for the Kabila-Sudan
alliance," the two leaders said in a joint communique issued in
Rwakitura, Uganda Tuesday, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
But Sudan denied any involvement in the Congo Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kagame had gone to Rwakitura, Museveni's farm, on Monday to
discuss with him the on-going crisis in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The statement issued at the end of the meeting commended
efforts being made in search of a solution to the crisis in Congo
(K) where Tutsi-led rebels revolted since August 2 and now still
occupy large tracts of territory in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
Uganda also reiterated the purpose of its presence in Congo,
saying, "the military presence of Uganda in the Democratic
Republic of Congo is based on genuine and legitimate security
interests and on its determination to prevent genocide."
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda continues to face insecurity caused by former Rwanda
armed forces (ex-Far)" and "Interahamwe militia based in the
Democratic Republic of Congo and supported by the Kabila
government," RNA quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda also Charged the Kabila regime with carrying out the
state-inspired acts of genocide and ethnic cleansing of targeted
groups of people in Democratic Congo.
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda reiterated its resolve to deal with the above concerns
using all appropriate means," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia sent troops to stop the rebels'
marching on capital Kinshasa and drive them out of the west in
late August, and Chad also sent troops to help Kabila fight the
rebels in the east.
</P>
<P>
At the end of their meeting the two leaders called for a
negotiated settlement of the conflict through talks that would
involve the government in Kinshasa, the Congolese rebels, and
opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
So far Kabila refuses to have direct talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
All the resolution of the Congo crisis must "address in an
acceptable and sustainable way, the legitimate interests of all
the neighboring states," the two leaders said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
