<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2110GMT, October 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EREZ BORDER CROSSING -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Wednesday substantial progress had been made in an
extended trilateral meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference after more than four hours of talks at
the border crossing between Israel and the Gaza Strip, Albright
said the extended meeting was "important and very productive."
</P>
<P>
She said that she found in the meeting a "new spirit," a
spirit of cooperation and a strong sense of urgency, on both
sides. She described the spirit as "quite helpful" and wished it
will be carried onto the Washington summit, which she announced
will be held on October 15 between Netanyahu, Arafat and
U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Significant and substantial progress" has been made in the
meeting on various issues including the further Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank, the security cooperation, the opening of the
Gaza airport and industrial park.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians also agreed to form a joint
committee monitoring anti-Israel incitement in Palestinian
education system and media, and to activate a people-to-people
program. (Netanyahu-Arafat-Albright-2nd writethru)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Wednesday that progress was made in his talks with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told a news conference that progress was made in
three areas: opening an industrial park in the Gaza Strip with
Israel's security concerns addressed, forming a committee
monitoring what he said the Palestinians' anti-Israel incitement
in education and media and activating person-to-person program
between Israel and the Palestinians.
(Israel-Netanyahu-Talks Progress-1st writethru)
</P>
<P>
