</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said
Wednesday that Iran would not give up the right to use force
against the Afghan Taliban militia for the killing of nine Iranian
diplomats and reporter.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that before the use of force, the Taliban would submit
to the demands of the international community and Iran" to punish
the killers, return the bodies of other three slain Iranians, and
release all captured Iranians, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here that Iran hoped to solve the
issue through diplomatic means and welcomed the visit to the
region by Lakhdar Brahimi, the special envoy of the U.N. Secretary
General on Afghan affairs. (Iran-Afghanistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said here
Wednesday that his government might request parliamentary consent
for a war with Syria, although war is still not desired.
</P>
<P>
Addressing deputies in the parliament following a cabinet
meeting to determine Turkey's policy towards Syria, Yilmaz said
that "we are not trying to create a war with Syria. The real
objective is to safeguard Turkey's vital interests."
</P>
<P>
