<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daughter of Indonesia's Soekarno Opens PDI Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A congress of the Indonesian
Democratic Party (PDI) led by Megawati Soekarnoputri, the daughter
of founding president Soekarno, opened in Denpasar, Bali, with a
commitment to establish a just government.
</P>
<P>
Opening the congress, Megawati said her party would establish a
just government which would not hesitate to uphold justice, after
the next general elections scheduled for May next year.
</P>
<P>
According to Antara news agency, Megawati, 51, proposed a
five-point political package for discussion at the congress which
will last until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The five points are loyalty to the 1945 constitution and the
Pancasila state ideology, priority to the people's sovereignty,
promotion of human rights, maintaining national unity and
integrity, and the implementation of independent and active
political systems.
</P>
<P>
Pancasila is the five basic principles of the Republic of
Indonesia -- the belief in the one and only god, just and
civilized humanity, the unity of Indonesia, democracy guided by
the inner wisdom in the unanimity arising out of deliberations
amongst representatives, social justice for the whole of the
people of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Among those who attended the opening ceremony of the congress
were Bali governor Dewa Made Bratha, retired generals grouped in
the National Front Kemal Idris, Edy Sudradjat and Ali Sadikin.
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors of South Africa and Brazil and 13 other
representatives of foreign missions in Indonesia also attended the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bali police chief Brig. Gen. Gunawan said the
opening ceremony of the three-day congress went smoothly and
orderly.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 police officers plus 1,400 military personnel have
been deployed to tighten security for the event. The local chapter
of Megawati's camp has recruited 1,000 supporters as security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
The conflict-ridden PDI is the second largest opposition party
in Indonesia. Megawati was ousted two years ago as leader of the
PDI in a move backed by the Soeharto government.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who replaced the late Soekarno in 1965, was himself
forced out of office on May 21 this year in a wave of public anger
and bloody riots amid the Asian economic crisis which plunged
Indonesia into its worst recession in decades.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in August, a congress was held by the government-backed
PDI in Palu, Central Sulawesi, and elected Budi Hardjono as new
chairman of the party.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the congress' agenda of Megawati's faction
included a change in its name from PDI, a prerequisite before it
can register with the Ministry of Home Affairs, formally separate
itself from Budi's camp and become a party eligible for the
general election.
</P>
<P>
However, a member of the congress' steering committee, Sabam
Sirait, said the change in the party's name would not be formally
included in the agenda.
</P>
<P>
"It's up to the government whether they will recognize
Megawati's PDI or not. But I'm confident that the government will
positively respond to the aspiration of the people who support
Megawati," Sirait said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
