<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans To Modernize Postal Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The State Post Bureau of China
plans to build more than 200 new post offices in the next two
years to modernize itself and open more routes, add vehicles and
update technology to speed up delivery, according to Liu Liqing,
the bureau's director.
</P>
<P>
China's postal service will purchase 40,000 automobiles, three
aircraft, 670 railway cars, and a great number of automatic
letter-sorting and parcel-sorting machines. The number of
computerized postal service counters will be increased to around
20,000, Liu told s meeting today for World Post Day on October 9.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that China's postal service is being challenged by
more privately-owned express delivery companies and the new
electronic communication at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
China has 2.6 million kilometers of postal routes and more than
80,000 post offices, with income tops 30 billion yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
China's postal service has more than 30,000 vehicles for
express mails and about 600 railway cars, and operates two air
routes. Its information network for express service covers over
200 cities and connects to some 30 countries and regions, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
China's postal service has established direct relations with
145 countries and regions and has issued stamps jointly with the
United States, Thailand, France, Switzerland, Sweden, Singapore,
Canada and other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
