<HEADLINE> Russia, Palestine Discuss Ways Out of Middle East Stalemate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Thursday kicked off his official visit to Russia and talked with
Russian President Boris Yeltsin on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat proposed to Yeltsin that Russia, as a co-sponsor of the
Middle East peace process, take part in a U.S.-Palestinian-Israeli
meeting in Washington scheduled for October 15.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinian leadership was interested in a more
active Russian involvement in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Arafat also discussed relations between their
countries and recent tension between Syria and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Arafat he would appoint an official -- most
likely a deputy foreign minister -- to deal with Middle East
issues and make regular visits to the region's capitals.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Arafat held behind-closed-door talks with
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Valentina Matviyenko. There was no
public statement of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, Interfax quoted well-informed sources as reporting
that the two leaders discussed ways out of the stalemate in the
peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"The sides also focused on matters related to the expansion of
ties between Russia and Palestine based on lasting traditions of
friendship and many-sided cooperation," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Palestine also signed an agreement on trade and
economic cooperation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Russian Trade Minister Georgy
Gabunia and Palestinian Culture and Education Minister Yasser Abd
Rabbu, according to the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
