<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Regrets Seleznyov's Call for Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
expressed "regret" in connection with the statement by State Duma
Chairman Gennady Seleznyov calling for a referendum on confidence
in the president, presidential press secretary Dmitry Yakushkin
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov called for a referendum on the removal of the
Russian president at a press conference on Thursday, a day after
the nationwide protest actions, during which the main political
demand was for the president's early resignation.
</P>
<P>
According to Seleznyov, "after this large-scale action of
protest which took place on Wednesday it would be more legitimate
to call a referendum in Russia on whether society trusts or does
not trust the president, on whether the president should or should
not resign."
</P>
<P>
However, on ORT television program, Yakushkin stressed that
most demands made in the course of the protest actions on
Wednesday were the payment of wages and pensions.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a call for referenda amounts to "shifting the
question into a wrong sphere". This could "result in the
unnecessary intensification of politicization in society and
departure from the resolution of specific issues", Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Selezynov also declared that he may
run for president and was ready to head the center-left bloc.
</P>
<P>
To Seleznyov's statement, Yeltsin "reacted calmly", saying that
it was not "either the first or the last statement", and the
president thinks there will be many statements of this sort in the
month to come, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Yukushkin also noted that during Thursday's meeting with
security ministers and the newly appointed generals in the
Kremlin, Yeltsin once again stressed that he would remain in
office until the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
