<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Claims Climb Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. first-time claims
for unemployment increased slightly last week amid a gloomy global
economic outlook, the Labor Department said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The number of first-time claims for unemployment benefits rose
by 11,000 to a seasonally adjusted 300,000, the first increase in
four weeks, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
However, a more closely watched four-week average of
unemployment claims dropped slightly by 3,500 to 295,750 for the
period ended one week earlier, the lowest point since 1989.
</P>
<P>
Through most of this year, a spending spree by American
consumers has helped insulate U.S. companies from economic
problems spreading from Asia to other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan this week noted he
expects the economic prospect not optimistic in the country as a
result of the wide-spread crisis abroad.
</P>
<P>
That means from farms to factories, workers will be more
vulnerable to job losses caused by dampening U.S. export sales and
a flood of cheap foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment so far remains near a generational low, but rose a
bit, to 4.6 percent, in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photo Exhibition of Late Chinese President Opens In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Library opened a photo
exhibition today to mark the 100th anniversary of late Chinese
President Liu Shaoqi's birth.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition has 300 photos, a number of objects, and
publications and video documents recording the life of this great
proletariat revolutionary, statesman, theorist, and leader of the
Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shaoqi was born in Ningxiang County in Hunan Province on
November 24, 1898. He rose to the position of president in the
late 1950s and early 1960s and was called a "public servant
to the people" for his contributions to China's revolution and
construction.
</P>
<P>
After Beijing, the exhibition will make a two-month visit to
Shaanxi, Sichuan, Henan, and Guangdong provinces, the cities of
Tianjin and Dalian, and some other cities.
</P>
<P>
The event is being sponsored by the Ministry of Culture, Party
School of the CPC Central Committee, Party Literature Research
Center of the CPC Central Committee, and Party History Research
Center of the CPC Central Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian, Iranian FMs Discuss Syrian-Turkish Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa held talks Thursday with visiting Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharazzi on the ongoing Syrian-Turkish tensions.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian Foreign Ministry spokesman said the talks between the
two ministers centered on Turkey's "provocative and aggressive
stances" against Syria.
</P>
<P>
They discussed the role of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) in helping defuse the Damascus-Ankara tensions,
said the spokesman, speaking on customary condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Kharazzi arrived here earlier Thursday. He came here with the
aim of mediating between Syria and Turkey, the two OIC member
states. Iran is holding the OIC presidency.
</P>
<P>
Damascus and Ankara have long been at odds over issues
including the alleged Syrian support for Turkey's Kurdish rebels,
Turkey's close military cooperation with Israel and water sharing.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of sheltering its outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party, which has been fighting since 1984 for an
independent state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
It has reportedly massed troops backed by tanks and heavy
artillery along the border with Syria, sparking fears for a
regional military conflict.
</P>
<P>
Syria has denied Turkey's charge and called for a diplomatic
solution to the disputes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Syria has criticized Turkey, a predominantly Muslim
country, for forging a military alliance with Israel, which it
said would endanger the Middle East peace and stability, and its
bargaining position in negotiations with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Iran also opposes the Turkish-Israeli military ties. Kharazzi
told a news conference in Tehran Wednesday that Iran "condemns
such an alliance on the grounds that it constitutes a threat to
the security of the region."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the existing differences between Syria and
Turkey do not justify Turkey's military buildup along the Syrian
border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
