<HEADLINE> Seminar On China's New Foreign Exchange Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration of
Foreign Exchange (SAFE) held a seminar October 7-8 to explain
recently enacted regulations on foreign exchange to
representatives of 11 foreign banks and foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
It was presided over by Li Fuxiang, deputy director of SAFE.
</P>
<P>
As the Southeast Asian economic crisis spreads, the
international financial sector is facing serious difficulties and
tough challenges, Li told the seminar, and said that China, as a
developing country, has an urgent need to improve its laws,
regulations, and controls to safeguard the long-term interests of
banks and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Those present expressed their understanding and support for the
new regulations, but also raised questions about the difficulties
that may arise out of trying to enforce them.
</P>
<P>
SAFE officials said that they will make improvements in
various parts of the regulations and keep communications channels
open.  
</P>
</TEXT>
