<HEADLINE> Biggest Ever Beijing Marathon Opens Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua)-- The biggest ever Beijing
International Marathon race is to start off at the Tian'anmen
Square on Saturday, with a record of over 19,000 runners
participating, a Chinese sports official announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The 1998 Beijing marathon will be the biggest ever in the
meet history as far as the number of the participants are
concerned," General Secretary of the Chinese Athletics
Association Shang Xiutang told the press.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing race was granted as the highiest standard marathon
in China by IAAF and AIMS in 1981 and has been held yearly ever
since.
</P>
<P>
"Now an unprecedented total of 19,422 runners from 30
countries and regions have been entered for the race," Shang
said.
</P>
<P>
The race is divided into four distances to contend with 914
men and women's athletes running the 42.195-km full course, while
the rest to run the half marathon, 10km and mini-marathon.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Hu Gangjun of China and Abebe Mekonnen of
Ethopia, who equaled the meet record in 1988 with a time of
2:07:35 set by Japanese Kodama Taisuke in 1986, will take part in
the race.
</P>
<P>
The prize money for the man's winner will be 20,000 U.S.
dollars with women's award 10,000.
</P>
<P>
"The prize money on offer is encouraging. "said Dickson
A.Kimetto Mochi, the coach of the high-flying Kenya outfit. "We
have complete confidence to achieve amazing performances."
</P>
<P>
Hu Gangjun, who recorded his personal best marathon of 2:09:18
last year, did not show enough fighting spirits as he was
sidelined for a year due to injuries.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the competition serves as my warm-up for the Asian
Games in December," said Hu, who recovered from his injuris for
only three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
