<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Beefs Up to 8,900 Against US Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah, after
breaking through the 10,000 psychological mark against the U.S.
dollar on Wednesday, closed at 8,900/9,000 rupiah to the dollar on
Thursday, the highest level since former president Soeharto
resigned in May.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian currency is now trading below the government and
International Monetary Fund's year-end target of 10,000 rupiah per
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Local currency dealers said fresh market talk of a possible
imposition of capital controls, hopes of a slowdown in inflation
rises and regional market strength helped boost the rupiah
standing.
</P>
<P>
A local bank's chief dealer said: "Among those factors, I think
the bullish trend in the regional markets is the dominant factor
behind the rupiah's strong gain."
</P>
<P>
The rupiah continued to gather steam after breaking the
resistance level of 10,600 to the U.S. dollar on Tuesday and
hitting the 10,000 mark on Wednesday, closing at 9,400 rupiah per
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"It is just a psychological game. The rupiah could easily gain
ground after it has broken several psychological barriers," the
chief dealer was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the government was considering tightening
the monitoring of capital flows into and out of the country. The
news had encouraged some offshore players, especially those with
short rupiah positions, to unload their U.S. dollar holdings to
cover their future rupiah obligations.
</P>
<P>
Achjar, Ilyas, a senior official of the central bank, Bank
Indonesia, said a draft on foreign exchange control had already
been prepared and its implementation is only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah was also boosted by continued U.S. dollar selling on
the part of state banks, the currency dealers said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Central Bureau of Statistics, the country's
inflation stood at 3.75 percent in September, much lower than
August's 6.30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the sidelines of a meeting of trade ministers from
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations in Manila, Indonesian
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar
Kartasasmita Wednesday said confidence was returning to the
rupiah.
</P>
<P>
But he warned against an overly sharp appreciation in the
currency and said the government wants to see a gradual
appreciation in the currency. "For instance, we don't want to see
the rupiah jump to 8,000," he added.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah was traded at 8,000 to the U.S. dollar in early May
but plummeted to 12,000 just days before the downfall of Soeharto
on May 21. Since then, the rupiah continued to weakened to 16,000.
</P>
<P>
The currency started to stage a recovery in July, when
multilateral financial institutions and donor countries pledged to
pump in billions of U.S. dollars in loans.
</P>
<P>
As the government, through state banks, converts U.S. dollars
to rupiah, the local currency has steadily risen.
</P>
<P>
According to Bank Indonesia Governor Sjahril Sabirin, the
government converted up to 15 million U.S. dollars daily in its
effort to stabilize the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The currency is also benefiting from the signs of waning social
unrest and anti-government demonstrations, the Jakarta Post said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
