<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portuguese Writer Wins 1998 Nobel Literature Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese writer Jose
Saramago, the 76-year-old novelist and poet, won the 1998 Nobel
Literature Prize, the Swedish Academy announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Saramago, who's works have been translated into 25 languages,
is the first writer in Portuguese to receive the world's most
prized literary award.
</P>
<P>
Saramago, "who with parables sustained by imagination,
compassion and irony, continually enables us once again to
apprehend an elusory reality", said the Academy.
</P>
<P>
Saramago was born in a family of farmers in Northern Lisbon.
Too poor to pay for high school, he had to abandon his studies and
train as a mechanic. After trying different jobs in the civil
service, he worked for a publishing company for 12 years and then
for newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Saramago wrote his first novel in 1947 and became famous in
1982 with the blasphemous and humorous story "Memorial do
Convento".
</P>
<P>
The book was described by the late Italian film-maker Federico
Fellini, a lover of exuberant images, as one of the most
interesting he had ever read.
</P>
<P>
The story, a fantasy about two lovers trying to escape the
Inquisition in a flying machine, was turned into an opera and
performed at Milan's La Scala in 1990 with the title of "Baltasar
and Blimunda".
</P>
<P>
Another of his books, "The Year of the Death of Ricardo Reis",
which was published in 1984, is a surreal story of a doctor-poet
and fascism's rise in 1936.
</P>
<P>
After his literary successes in the 1980s, he devoted himself
to writing.
</P>
<P>
Saramago is married to a Spanish journalist and lives in
Lanzarote in the Canary Islands.
</P>
<P>
The literature prize was the first Nobel Prize announced for
1998. The cash award for each prize category this year is about
7.6 million Swedish krona (almost one million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The prize was established in the will of Alfred Nobel, a Swede
who invented dynamite and died in 1896. The prizes, along with
diplomas and gold medals, are presented to the winners every year
on December 10, the anniversary of Nobel's death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Imports, Exports Fall in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's exports and
imports both fell significantly in July from a year earlier,
official external trade statistics showed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Total exports in July dropped by 10 percent in volume compared
with the same month of 1997, and total imports fell by 14 percent,
the Census and Statistics Department said.
</P>
<P>
In July, re-exports went down by 11 percent and domestic
exports shrank by eight percent on a year-on-year basis.
Re-exports of fuels, raw materials, semi-manufactures, consumer
commodities and capital goods registered considerable decreases
during the month, while those of foodstuffs jumped by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports of footwear and metal ores and scrap slumped
by 44 percent and 40 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Notable drops in import volumes were recorded for foodstuffs,
consumer goods, raw materials, semi-manufactures and fabrics,
while imports of fuels increased by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of 1998, total exports went down
1.4 percent compared with the same period of last year, and
imports retreated 3.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
