<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder to Meet Clinton on Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- German chancellor-elect Gerhard
Schroeder will go to Washington to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Friday, Schroeder's Social Democratic Party (SPD) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder will be accompanied by Joschka Fischer, a leader of the
Greens party who is tipped as the prospective foreign minister in a
possible SPD-Greens coalition government. Also on the trip is SPD's
expert on foreign affairs, Guenther Verheugen, who could become
defence minister in Schroeder's government.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the talks in the White House, Schroeder is also due
to meet World Bank President James Wolfensohn Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The one-day Washington visit is Schroeder's second foreign trip
since he won the German general election on September 27 which ended
the 16 years of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's leadership.
</P>
<P>
To dispel fears about any major change in Germany's European
policy, Schroeder already paid a visit to Paris a week ago during
which he reassured French leaders that his government would maintain
the traditional partnership with France.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, during his Washington visit Schroeder is expected to
reaffirm Bonn's commitment to the trans-Atlantic alliance.
</P>
<P>
German press reports said that Schroeder is set to face an early
test of his foreign policy leadership in Washington when he holds
talks with Clinton on such key issues as possible military action in
the Serbian province of Kosovo and the crisis in global financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. stance on possible air strikes in Kosovo could face strong
opposition from Germany's pacifist Greens, which is currently the only
candidate with which Schroeder is negotiating to form a coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
The Greens opposes German participation in any NATO military action
in Kosovo without a U.N. resolution approving the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Germany's independent central bank, the Bundesbank, also
differs with Washington on how wealthy industrial nations should move
to avert a global economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to call on Schroeder to show leadership on all
these issues, diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
However, technically, Schroeder is not yet German chancellor at the
moment. He is due to be elected by Germany's new parliament on October
27 provided that his SPD and the Greens wind up their coalition talks
in time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
