<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Telecommunications Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- In the past decade, China had
rapid growth in the telecommunications industry and China has the
second largest number of phones after the United States, with 100
million phones.
</P>
<P>
Earnings of China's telecommunications sector have increased
sharply from 1.25 billion yuan (151 million U.S. dollars) in 1978
to 182.8 billion yuan in 1997 and the communication network is one
of the largest in the world. There are fewer than 20 cities in the
world using 8-digit phone numbers, and seven are in China.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, it took one or two days to make a long distance call
in China, but today, there is an analogue mobile
telecommunications network covering most of China and a modern
digital network for more than 250 cities and 1,170 counties.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has encouraged investment in
telecommunications infrastructure since 1978, and 6.56 billion
U.S. dollars worth of foreign loans have been used for advanced
technology and microwave satellite communication.
</P>
<P>
Income of China's post and telecommunications sector in 1997
was 177.3 billion yuan, a 150-fold increase from 1978, with
profits of 40 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
