<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blood Pressure Study To Prevent Hypertension in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Doctors say that there should be
a nationwide survey of blood pressure in China to make the public
more aware of disease prevention.
</P>
<P>
"At least 70 percent of adults should have their blood pressure
checked to reveal hypertension patients as soon as possible," says
Wu Yingkai, of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the fact that there are 100 million people with
hypertension in China, more than 70 percent of them do not know
they have the disease, according to a survey of 940,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Another study found that, for hypertension patients who failed
to have the disease treated, 70 to 80 percent ultimately died of a
stroke, and about 15 percent died of coronary heart disease or
kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
In fact, 75 percent of these problems can be brought under
control if people adopt a healthy lifestyle and take preventive
measures, says Prof. Liu Lisheng, the chairwoman of the Chinese
Hypertension League.
</P>
<P>
One plan calls for people above the age of 35 who visit the
doctor for any reason to be given a blood pressure
check. Hypertension control work will win more policy and
financial support from the government so the public can be more
aware of the disease, says Yin Dakui, vice-minister of health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0104 </DOCNO>
