<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Hotel Occupancy Rate May Rise Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The occupancy rate in
Indonesia's hotels is expected to improve to 42 percent next year,
the head of Indonesia's hoteliers organization said.
</P>
<P>
"The figure would be 2 percent higher than this year's 40
percent but 15 percent lower than last year's 57 percent," said
Diyak Mulahela, chairman of the Jakarta Association of Hotel
Controllers.
</P>
<P>
Mulahela attributed the low rate to foreign tourists' fears
following May's riots in Indonesia, Antara news agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The country saw the worst looting and rioting in decades in
Jakarta, Medan and Solo from May 13 to 15. More than 1,200 lives
were claimed, and thousands of buildings and vehicles were damaged
or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Data collected by Antara showed that the occupancy rate among
star-rated hotels in Jakarta dropped from 50-60 percent during
normal times to only 25-30 percent in May-August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
