<HEADLINE> Vietnam PM Urges More Efforts for Street Children Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan Van
Khai has urged officials in the countryside to make more efforts
to take in homeless children from HANOI and Ho Chi Minh City and
stop their drift to major cities, official media reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of street children are arriving in urban
centers causing social problems which call for an urgent solution,
and immediate action should also be taken to stop them from
begging at garbage dumps and making nuisances at tourist sites,
Khai told a two-day national conference on street children held
this week in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that there are about 16,000 homeless
children in Vietnam, over 6,000 of them living in Ho Chi Minh City
and nearly 3,000 in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that despite some measures to solve the
problem, the number of street children moving from rural areas to
cities remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The sexual abuse of children, the exploitation of their labor
and their violation of laws were painful for the whole society, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the conference discussed ways to stop homeless
children from moving to urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Official reports said Khai proposed short- and long-term
solutions to the problem and asked the sponsors of the conference
to make policy research on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
