<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Banks' Bad Loans Estimated at 115 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The bad loans held by South Korean banks
are estimated at 160 trillion won (some 115.9 billion U.S. dollars) as
of June this year, the Korea Institute of Finance said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The loans, calculated in accordance with international guidelines
for bad loan classification, exceed the 120 trillion won (about 86.9
billion ) previously calculated by South Korean standards.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the South Korean classifications of bad loans, international
standards takes into account the ability of borrowers to repay loans.
</P>
<P>
The international guideline, which South Korea agreed with the
International Monetary Fund to adopt by January next year, focuses on
the overall financial health of corporate borrowers.
</P>
<P>
A loan is considered a default in South Korea when it is at
least three months overdue. The three-month classification took
effect July 1 this year, updating the previous standard of a six
month default period.
</P>
<P>
Bad loans are a major reason triggering the ongoing financial
crisis in South Korea, threatening the viability of banks and other
financial institutions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The much-larger-than-expected bad loans calls for an
enlargement of public fund injections needed to bail out faltering
banks, the institute said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The government will likely have to increase the 64 trillion won
(some 46.4 billion U.S. dollars) rescue fund earmarked for bank
recapitalization and bad loan purchases.
</P>
<P>
The institute proposed the ideal rescue fund level at about 87
trillion won (roughly 63 billion U.S. dollars), 36 percent more
than the currently established fund.
</P>
<P>
The latest estimate highlights the seriousness of bad loan
problems in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Seoul borrowed a bailout loan of 58 billion U.S. dollars from
the International Monetary Fund last December after it was plagued
by a financial crisis due to corporate bankruptcies and bad loans
of financial institutions late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
