<HEADLINE> U.S. Mediation Continues, Netanyahu Seeking Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross continued his mediation in the region Thursday as
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is seeking support from
his coalition partners on the eve of a U.S. summit.
</P>
<P>
Ross met with Israeli cabinet secretary Danny Naveh and
senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat to discuss interim
issues, especially the opening of the Palestinian airport in
Gaza, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The airport has been a contentious point between the two
sides for the past 18 months, mainly due to Israeli security
concerns. U.S. officials have said that Ross will try to wrap
up an understanding on the opening of the airport before he
leaves the region Friday.
</P>
<P>
Washington would like to see as many preliminary
understandings as possible reached before the summit between
Netanyahu, Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser
Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
Following four hours of talks with Netanyahu and Arafat,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced Wednesday
that the summit will start next Thursday. White House said that
the summit will be held at the Wye Plantation in Maryland, where
Israeli and Syrian negotiators met for the first face-to-face
talks three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Albright also said that substantial progress has been made
on various issues during the trilateral talks held on the Erez
border crossing between Israel and Gaza. She hailed a "new
spirit" on both leaders which she said would be helpful for
the summit.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and
senior security officials met in Tel Aviv with George Tenet,
head of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), to discuss
Israeli demands that the PNA take measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The CIA is trying to bring the two sides closer for an
understanding on security cooperation, which some said is one
of the main problems remaining unresolved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu convened his "kitchen cabinet" Thursday to
brief the other three members -- Mordechai, National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon, and Industry and Trade Minister Natan
Sharansky -- on his talks with Arafat Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Netanyahu has invited the three ministers
to the U.S. summit. It has been reported that Netanyahu
intends to appoint Sharon, the leading hardline minister in his
cabinet, as foreign minister in exchange for his support if an
agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also met with leaders of the National
Religious Party (NRP), a far-right coalition partner, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The NRP has threatened to topple the government if
Netanyahu makes wide range of concessions to the Palestinians.
Its leaders also demanded that Education Minister Yitzhak Levy,
a NRP member, to be invited to go to the U.S. with
Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
