<HEADLINE> China Still Has Hope For 8 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- China's GDP this year is
expected to grow by about 8 percent, with negative inflation,
according to an autumn report of the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The report says that agriculture added value will grow by 3.2
percent, manufacturing by 9.2 percent, and service by 8.3 percent
and faster economic development is expected in 1999, with 8.6
percent growth.
</P>
<P>
China has actually attained this year's macroeconomic goals, it
says, with a reverse in the downward trend in economic growth, the
stable exchange rate, and a stable unemployment situation.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, the national economy is expected to have
higher growth. Fixed assets this year will grow by 16.3 percent
over 1997 to 2.88 trillion yuan (about 346.9 billion US dollars)
and in 1999 it will be 3.33 trillion yuan (about 401.2 billion US
dollars), up 14.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
There will be negative growth in retail prices this year, but
it will return to 1.7 percent next year, with the implementation
of a more active financial policy and growing domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales in 1998 and 1999 will grow by 8.7 and 8.6 percent,
respectively, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
China's exports will slow down, but foreign trade will have a
surplus. The Chinese currency yuan is expected to remain stable in
1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
