<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Higher Cancer Rate in Xinjiang Sheer Fabrication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese radiation and medical
experts reassured the world today that past nuclear tests in the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region did not cause radiation pollution
leading to a rising cancer rate among local residents, as
reported by some members of the British media.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the newspaper Independent and the British Channel
Four have presented stories claiming that Xinjiang in western
China has a higher incidence of cancer, a higher mortality rate,
and more cases of congenital malformation than other parts of
China, due to radiation exposure from nuclear testing carried out
there between 1964 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the Radiation Medical Institute in the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region suggests that the additional
amount of radiation received by local people is only 2.9 percent
of the annual dose caused by natural radiation.
</P>
<P>
The institute also carried out an investigation of
radiation-related epidemics during the 1974-1984 period among
people living within a 120- kilometer range of the nuclear testing
ground. Of the 542,784 investigated cases, deaths caused by cancer
were 55.51:100,000 a year; while the rate in the comparison group
was 59.09:100,000.
</P>
<P>
The two figures are approximately the same in terms of
statistics, according to experts. Therefore the British news
reports hardly hold water when they say the cancer incidence in
Xinjiang is 39 percent higher than in other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
According to three comprehensive surveys carried out between
the late 1960s and 1990 by the Industrial Hygiene Research
Institute under the Ministry of Health, in leeward regions of the
nuclear testing ground the nuclear tests did not produce any
negative effects on the health of residents.
</P>
<P>
Since it is positioned windward, Xinjiang could not have a
higher incidence rate of radiation-related illness, said the
experts, most of whom were involved in the surveys and
investigations.
</P>
<P>
The alleged higher cancer rate in Xinjiang is a sheer
fabrication and it is an act of irresponsibility for the British
media to do such reporting, the experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
