to have more cuts in their interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) extended Wednesday's
gains by 29.39 points to 950.96 points at close.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover rose to 238.70 million units valued at
376.43 million Singapore dollars (230.09 million U.S. dollars).
Advancers led decliners by 128 to 73 with 219 counters unchanged..
</P>
<P>
Van DH was the most active stock of the day as it had a volume
of 38.46 million units traded. KepLand was the second most heavily
traded stock with a volume of 16.93 million units. KepCorp was
next with 11.01 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Transmarco led the ascent of the day with a rise of 76 cents to
2.96 Singapore dollars at close. SPH moved up 70 cents to end at
13.60 Singapore dollars. Thai Pr was up 60 cents to close at 2.70
U.S dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, GzhouInv was the biggest loser of the day as
it lost 70 cents to close at 0.70 Hong Kong dollars. Creative 50
was the second biggest loser of the day with a slide of 20 cents
to 14.10 Singapore dollars. Wepco 500 shed off 17 cents to end at
0.13 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Market was also encouraged by Wednesday's comments on the U.S.
economy by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan who raised
prospects of further interest rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan told the U.S. National Association of Business
Economics: "We are clearly facing a set of forces that should be
dampening demand going forward to an unknown extent."
</P>
<P>
"This is a time for monetary policy to be especially alert," he
warned. 
</P>
