<HEADLINE> Nigeria Invited to Commonwealth Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian delegation headed
by Foreign Minister Ignatius Olisemeka will attend a two-day
meeting of the Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group (CMAG) in
London Thursday, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The CMAG meeting is expected to assess the efforts by the
Nigerian government in democratization and protecting human
rights.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time since 1995 that Nigeria was invited to
the Commonwealth meeting, though visits by CMAG members and
bilateral dialog have been going on in the past.
</P>
<P>
Reports quoted sources from the Nigerian Foreign Ministry in
Abuja as saying that Olisemeka will during the meeting "address
efforts made by the Federal Government since June 9 to put
together and implement a credible transition program."
</P>
<P>
Olisemeka will also let CMAG know about the various efforts
made so far to redress the poor human rights records of the
previous administration which brought about the sanctions imposed
on Nigeria by the Commonwealth, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"He will definitely aim at arguing for a lift of the sanctions
placed on the country in 1995," they added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth in late 1995 after
the government of late General Sani Abacha hanged author Ken
Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority activists on charges of
murder.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth then established the CMAG to monitor the
situation in Nigeria to decide whether and when to resume
Nigeria's membership.
</P>
<P>
Bold efforts by Nigeria's new leader General Abdulsalam
Abubakar to democratize Nigeria and improve its human right
records, including a new transition to civil rule program and the
release of all politicE,$detainees, have won him the backing of
the west world, including the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
But it is believed that sanctions against Nigeria will last
until the new transition program ushers in an elected civilian
president in May next year as it was promised by the Abubakar
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
