<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Urges Private Sector to Help Ease Pressure of Economic Downturn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China, expressed
the hope Thursday that the private sector in Hong Kong do what it
can to help ease the pressure brought about by the economic
downturn.
</P>
<P>
"While the government has a clear responsibility to help Hong
Kong people face up to the current difficulties, I look also to
the private sector to do what it can to help ease the pressure on
the community," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not government's place to interfere in setting wage
levels and employment policies. But in these difficult times I
hope that employers will handle these issues with sensitivity," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Tung made the remarks Thursday when he spoke at a luncheon of
the Joint Chambers of Commerce to explain his Policy Address for
1998 delivered on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his Policy Address, Tung recounted the events of the past
year and outlined plans to respond to the challenges caused by the
financial turmoil and the bursting of Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
He also described how Hong Kong could turn its present
difficulties into opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the immediate job in hand is "to steer Hong Kong
towards economic recovery."
</P>
<P>
Tung said he believes that Hong Kong also needs to take account
of four main factors which will be crucial to its recovery, which
are: an improvement in the external, financial and economic
environment; a steadying of our interest rates here; stability in
the property market; and above all, a return of public confidence.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the year 1998 has been "a year of painful adjustment"
for Hong Kong, as property prices have fallen substantially and
lay-offs and wage adjustments are continuing as the city respond
to the effects of high interest rates and a slowdown in business
activity.
</P>
<P>
"This adjustment, although painful, is necessary as we fight to
regain our competitiveness," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"The signs are that 1999 will continue to be a difficult year,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said Hong Kong needs to devise short-term measures which
will cushion the impact of the downturn in this difficult economic
climate but in the same time has to draw up longer-term plans for
a sustained economic growth in the future.
</P>
<P>
"It is my belief that Hong Kong has the potential to be more
than simply one of the leading cities in our country. My vision is
for Hong Kong to have the same status in Asia as do New York and
London in North America and Europe respectively, and beyond that
to be truly one of the world's premier cities," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, Tung said, the regional financial crisis
and the bursting of Hong Kong's "bubble" economy have presented
"unprecedented challenges."
</P>
<P>
In face of these challenges "we have responded deliberately and
thoughtfully by introducing immediate measures to relieve pain and
stimulate growth, as well as developing longer-term strategies to
ensure solid expansion in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been criticism of the way in which we have responded
to certain crises that have occurred in the past year, such as the
avian influenza outbreak, the red tides and mishaps in the medical
sector as well as the opening of the airport. We accept that the
government itself could perform better in some areas, and we are
determined that we will improve our performance," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"The big issue now is our own confidence. We do face continued
problems in the near term. But we must not sell ourselves short,"
Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure, that as long as we maintain our self-confidence and
remain resilient, we will be able to turn these crises into
opportunity and together overcome the adversity that we now face."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
