<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Copper Giant Loses $63.3M During April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's mining conglomerate,
the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), has announced a net
loss of 126.6 billion Kwacha or 63.3 million U.S. Dollars in the
second quarter ending on June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM's company secretary Michael Mukwakwa announced the
mid-year financial results here Wednesday, saying that in
the same period last year, ZCCM registered a profit of 17.4
billion Kwacha or 8.7 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
From April to June, the conglomerate's copper production
dropped by 11,201 tons at 67,207 tons compared to 78,408 tons in
the corresponding period of the previous year, Zambia Daily Mail
Thursday quoted Mukwakwa as saying.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall in production was largely attributed to the
exclusion of production from two privatized mines which produced
13,049 tons of copper in the same period last year, said
Mukwakwa.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM's cobalt production, however rose to 1,037 tons in the
second quarter from 996 tons in the same period last year due to
the combination of the continuous depreciation of the Kwacha and
the improved cobalt prices on the international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
