<HEADLINE> Chief Executive's Policy Address Welcomed in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa's second Policy Address, which he presented before the
Legislative Council Wednesday afternoon, was welcomed by local
media, communities and business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po published an editorial Thursday saying that Tung has
laid out long term as well as short term measures to deal with the
economic difficulties Hong Kong is facing and this will help
stimulate the domestic demand and raise citizens' confidence.
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao said in a commentary that the chief executive has
worked out ways of tackling the difficulties by means of facing
them squarely and analyzing the current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The ways Tung put forward for overcoming the current
difficulties are not unrealistic optimism or empty pledges but
based on the ground of objective analysis.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Commercial Daily described the Policy Address as
"calm, pragmatic, positive and confident."
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Economic Times said in a commentary that Tung can
adjust his policies according to the changed situation and in this
way the confidence of the citizens can be re-established.
</P>
<P>
In addition to local media, various communities and business
sectors also expressed their welcomes to Tung's Policy Address.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce said in a statement
that the Policy Address has laid a solid foundation for the
development of the current policies.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Trade Development Council welcomed Tung's remarks to
build Hong Kong into a major international cosmopolitan city in
Asia while the Hong Kong productivity Council hailed Tung's
proposals to promote the innovation and technology in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
HongKong Telecom, the largest telecommunications corporation in
Hong Kong, expressed its support for the government's
determination and speed in implementing its policies related to
Information Technology.
</P>
<P>
Teachers and people in the profession of education said they
were encouraged by the government's large amount of resources on
education despite the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
The Securities and Futures Commission welcomed the measures
laid out by the chief executive in his Policy Address about
maintaining and strengthening Hong Kong's status as an
international financial center and said the commission will give
full support to these measures.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong expressed its
support for the establishment of the second market.
</P>
<P>
Other proposals in the Policy Address on boosting tourism,
stabilizing the property prices, improving quality of life were
also welcomed.
</P>
<P>
Some people said they were disappointed that the chief
executive has few "immediate" measures to turn around the current
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
However, many citizens said it's not realistic for Hong Kong to
recover immediately while the economy in the whole Asia is in
recession and they hope the government will take concrete steps to
implement these policies laid out by Tung. 
</P>
</TEXT>
