<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Security Adviser Visits Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. National
Security Adviser, Anthony Lake, arrived here Thursday to try to
facilitate a peaceful solution to the on-going Ethio-Eritrean
conflict.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. Ambassador to Ethiopia, David Shinn,
Lake has finished a similar mission in the Eritrean capital Asmara.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been mediating in the conflict between Ethiopia
and Eritrea soon after the border conflict between the two
countries erupted in May this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., together with Rwanda, formulated a proposal which
requires the withdrawal of Eritrean troops from Badme/Shiraro
border areas which were administered by Ethiopia before May 12,
1998.
</P>
<P>
But Eritrea refused to withdraw its forces from the disputed
border areas, saying that its troops " merely retook" areas which
had been illegally occupied by the Ethiopian forces.
</P>
<P>
Lake's visit to Eritrea and Ethiopia came one week before the
October 15 meeting in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, of the Heads of
State Committee set up by the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
to mediate in the Ethio-Eritrean conflict.
</P>
<P>
The committee, composed of the presidents of Burkina Faso,
Zimbabwe, Djibouti and Rwanda, will examine the findings of their
ambassadors who visited Asmara and Addis Ababa in July to
ascertain the status of the Badme/Shiraro areas before the border
dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
