<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Interest Rates Cut by 0.25 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England provided a
degree of relief for Britain's industry by announcing a cut in
interest rates by 0.25 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The nine members of the bank's Monetary Policy Committee
decided to reduce the base rate from 7.5 percent to 7.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the past months both employers and trade unions had
repeatedly called on the Bank of England to urgently lower its rates
to avoid a recession.
</P>
<P>
However, economic analysts warn that the cut may be too small to
stimulate a flagging U.K. and world economy.
</P>
<P>
It was a difficult decision for Britain's central bank to make,
though, because the country's economy is not moving in lockstep.
While manufacturing is already in recession, the service sector is
still booming.
</P>
<P>
But high interest rates translate into a strong pound, and that
is making British products expensive. Many exporters have already
warned that the strong pound has forced them to close production
lines as demand from abroad has slackened.
</P>
<P>
The pound had already weakened against the German currency, the
Deutschmark, in anticipation of a rate cut. One pound bought around
2.75 DM on Thursday, as opposed to over 3DM earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
Millions of home owners will rejoice as well as mortgage lenders
are expected to pass the rate cut on to their customers, resulting
in lower mortgage payments.
</P>
<P>
But there are worries that the bank, the industry and trade
unions may have miscalculated. Both earnings growth and domestic
demand are still strong enough to drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
"If Thursday's decision fuels inflation, then interest rates
will have to go up again. This would be a body blow to business
confidence," a BBC analyst said.
</P>
<P>
The UK Government has charged the Bank of England to hit an
inflation target of 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the rate cut may not be large enough to calm the
financial markets. Because of the turmoil on the world's stock
markets the small reduction of interest rates may not be enough to
make shares an attractive investment again.
</P>
<P>
Anticipating a small rate cut London shares had lost heavily in
the morning. Shortly before the bank announced its decision the FTSE
100 index was down more than 100 points to 4,724.
</P>
<P>
Last week, when the U.S. Federal Reserve cut one of its interest
rates by a quarter per cent, stock markets worldwide went into a
tailspin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
