<HEADLINE> Chinese Media More Dynamic in Market Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua writer Lin Gu
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- "I now feel like it's a dream
when I look back at a piece of tape I've made and hear my
commentary criticizing a local government, or a public security
bureau, a procuratorate. I never dreamed of commenting on
government only a few years back," said Fang Hongjin, the host of
Focus Report on China Central TV Station.
</P>
<P>
As a popular program attracting 300 million viewers every
night, Focus Report was applauded by Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji,
speaking as an ordinary viewer and supporter. "I'm also qualified
to be the target of your supervision, right? " said Zhu with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
Fang said that compared with the past, the most remarkable
progress is that we can speak out frankly on screen from the point
of view of the grass-roots people instead of preaching with a
stiff face.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that China's transition to a socialist market
economy is pushing official media organizations to promote reforms
in content, style and management.
</P>
<P>
Advertisements began to appear in the mass media after China
began focusing on economic development in 1978, and now there is
wider coverage of the economy, social reality and entertainment
which appeals to a broad audience.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese media today presents its readers and viewers with
dynamic choices, from matchmaking to the stock exchange, and from
street gossip to academic opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
