<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Media More Dynamic in Market Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua writer Lin Gu
</P>
<P>
Currently, China has 2,160 newspapers, compared with some 100
in 1978, and there are more than 2,000 TV and radio stations.
Heated competition has resulted in the emergence of media
conglomerates with economic clout and a wide range of business
interests.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Guangdong Provincial Committee of the
Communist Party of China, Southern Weekend is now the weekly
newspaper with the largest circulation in China.
</P>
<P>
The editor-in-chief of the weekly, Jiang Yiping, explained that
this success lies in their endeavor to expose social corruption,
protect the unfairly treated, and also focus on life and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily, the organ of the Chinese Communist Party,
is also being improved and now carries more and more information
and on-the-spot reporting and scoop news stories to meet the
demand of the readers, according to its president Shao Huaze.
</P>
<P>
Many local TV stations also present news analysis programs
similar to Focus Report, and have received the audience's
immediate applause.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Rongji pointed out that media's watchdog role is crucial to
the building of China's democratic and legal system. The media can
help us correct our mistakes, listen to the public opinion, and
encourage the people to keep our mission on track, Zhu said, and
called on Chinese journalists be the "voice of the people, mirror
of the government and pioneer of the reform."
</P>
<P>
Changes in the Chinese media today indicate that China is
stepping into a more open and confident age, stressed Yu Guomin,
deputy director of the Public Opinion Research Institute of
People's University of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
