<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo Following Previous Big Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo
Thursday with the Nikkei index losing 5.78 percent following
Wednesday's 803-point rise as the yen's sharp rise against the
U.S. dollar encouraged foreign investors to dump stocks across the
board.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 799.55 points, the
biggest single-day point decline this year, to end at 13,026.06.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 45.48 points or 4.34 percent to
1,001.50 after gaining 5 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section was brisk at an estimated 527
million shares, but down from Wednesday's 631.46 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic fall did not surprise traders. Many apparently
were not expecting the market to keep Wednesday's big gains for
long.
</P>
<P>
People who wanted to sell saw this as a good opportunity, a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Many export-reliant firms suffered due to continued volatility
in overseas stock markets and fears of a global economic
slowdown. The strong yen is also seen as a minus for exporters
because it reduces the value of their overseas earnings.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar recovered
slightly against the yen after plunging to the 120 level for the
first time in nearly one year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 122.35-38 yen at 5 p.m. (local
time), up from 121.80-85 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, and up from
120.75-85 yen late Wednesday in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
