<HEADLINE> Abubakar, Kabila Call for Withdrawal of Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) have called for the immediate withdrawal
of foreign troops from the DRC to pave the way for early
settlement of the crisis in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued Wednesday in Nigerian capital
Abuja, the two countries also called on Congo's neighboring
countries to respect the territorial integrity and sovereignty of
the DRC, according to the press reports here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique was issued after talks between Nigerian
Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar and his Congolese
counterpart President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders said that the withdrawal of foreign troops
would be a first step toward creating a conducive atmosphere for
the resolution to the crisis in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the Joint Commission between the two governments
would be held as early as possible to strengthen their cooperation,
said the joint communique.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed that effective bilateral and
regional economic cooperation among African countries was
necessary prerequisites for the continental economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Before ending his two-day official visit to Nigeria and
leaving for home Wednesday, President Kabila stressed, "It is our
prayer that Congo should be left alone on its way forward."
</P>
</TEXT>
