<HEADLINE> No Peace in Afghanistan without Broad-based </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Secretary General's
special envoy on Afghan affairs Lakhdar Brahimi stated here on
Thursday that no peace would exist in Afghanistan without
establishment of a broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi made the remark at a press conference while answering
Xinhua correspondent's question about the possibility to establish
a broad-based government in Afghanistan after the Afghan Taliban
militia occupied more than 90 percent the country's territory.
</P>
<P>
He said that a broad-based government should be established
in Afghanistan with the participation of all groups and factions.
</P>
<P>
"Without such a government, it is impossible for Afghanistan
to have a lasting peace," Brahimi said, adding that the Taliban
might occupy the whole Afghanistan, but that does not mean the
country would have peace.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the international community would work for the
benefit of the Afghan people, "so, the first thing is to stop the
human rights abuses in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy said that the second would be to reduce the
tension between Iran and the Taliban caused by the killing of a
group of Iranian diplomats and reporter in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The tension also imposed a threat to the whole region, he said,
adding that Iran's military buildup on its border with Afghanistan
proved the seriousness of the situation.
</P>
<P>
What is important for the international community is to defuse
the tension in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi said that the situation has not changed so far despite
of the efforts by the international community, particularly the
U.N., the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
He said that Iranian officials mentioned possible military
operations against the Taliban in the talks with him, but they
announced Iran prefers to settle the problem through political
means.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the possibility for the U.N. to recognize the
Taliban, Brahimi said that it was not the U.N. Secretary General
but the U.N. members that would decide whether to recognize the
Taliban or not.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy arrived here on Sunday, he would leave here for
Islamabad Thursday afternoon to meet Pakistani and Taliban
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
