<HEADLINE> Iran FM Off To Mediate Turkish-Syrian Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi left for Damascus Thursday morning to join in efforts to
mediate the mounting dispute between Syria and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Kharrazi told the official news agency
IRNA that Iran is ready to help bring about a diplomatic solution
to the ongoing tensions between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Ankara and Damascus have built up recently
after Turkey intensifies its accusation of Syria over its
supporting the Turkish Kurdish rebels who have been fighting
since 1984 for autonomy for the Kurdish minority in southeastern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has massed heavy troops along the borders with Syria,
for the first time, late last week to conduct military exercises.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has shuttled between Turkey
and Syria over the past few days to try to ease the tensions.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly said that enemies of Islam, especially the
Israelis, would benefit from any differences among Muslim states.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but politically secular state,
has close military ties with Israel, which incurred criticism from
the Arab world, especially Syria.
</P>
<P>
But many of the Arab states favored to unite with Turkey
instead of estranging it.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami also voiced Tehran's
readiness to mediate between Syria and Turkey Wednesday when
phoning his Syrian and Turkish counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi will hold talks with Syrian officials and then fly to
Ankara later Thursday to encourage the two countries to settle the
their differences peacefully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
