<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lebanon's President Selection Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The news that Army Commander
Emile Lahoud would become Lebanon's next president was quickly
welcomed and supported by the country's politicians and religious
figures alike.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Mohsen Dalloul welcomed the choice, saying
that for the first time, a president who enjoys the support of a
popular consensus, will arrive at Baabda, the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud's selection was in fact finalized on Monday by Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad and his outgoing Lebanese counterpart
Elias Hrawi in a marathon summit in Damascus. With 35,000 troops
as peacekeepers in Lebanon, Syria is the main power broker and
undisputed king-maker in the country.
</P>
<P>
Assad and Hrawi agreed at the meeting to amend the third clause
of Article 49 of Lebanon's Constitution, to clear the way for
Lahoud's ascendance to presidency. The clause stipulates that
first-rank civil servants wishing to join the presidential race
should quit their posts two years in advance of the vote.
</P>
<P>
If all goes as planned, Lahoud will be the 11th president of
Lebanon since its independence in 1943.
</P>
<P>
When the agreement on the army commander's choice was disclosed
after Hrawi's late night return from Damascus, Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri was the first to congratulate Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
From Riyadh where he was on a visit, Hariri telephoned the
general to say "Mabrouk (Congratulations), Mr President."
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that Lahoud had all the qualifications needed
to become the president, and was "the best choice."
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Nabih Berri, Hariri's on-and-off foe, was also
quick to declare unreserved support to Lahoud's selection, saying
the general would definitely be an honest arbiter who neutrally
oversees the power balance between state institutions.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, 62, a close ally of Syria, was appointed army commander
in November, 1989 on the eve of the end of Lebanon's 15-year-old
sectarian civil war.
</P>
<P>
He has gained popular support from many Lebanese, including
most politicians, due to his landmark achievements in rebuilding
the country's army into a cohesive fighting machine after its
tragic disintegration during the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Many hope that the reform-minded leader will introduce drastic
changes into political life which is described by opposition
parties as full of corruption.
</P>
<P>
Maronite Catholic patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir, the spiritual
head of Lebanon's largest Christian sect, said "the general is a
clean, disciplined leader with a sharp patriotic sentiment. I
bless the choice."
</P>
<P>
But he criticized the way the selection was made at the summit
talks which he said is "undemocratic." The predominantly rightist
Maronite community has long been resentful of Syria's grip on
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a public opinion poll conducted by a governmental agency,
Lahoud received a 53.4 percent support from all 2,500 Lebanese
from various regions and religions questioned at random.
</P>
<P>
Even for Lahoud's main challenger in the presidential race,
opposition parliament member Butros Harb also spoke highly of
Lahoud, saying he was qualified enough to lead the nation into the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the process of electing Lahoud as the new
president will start from Thursday cabinet session during which
the 68-year-old incumbent president, Hrawi, will propose a bill to
amend the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
After receiving the bill, the parliament will convene Thursday
next week to vote on the amendment and reconvene on October 15 to
elect Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
If everything goes as planned, analysts here said, the general
will take the oath of presidency on November 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Calls for Future-Oriented Ties With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae
Jung said here Thursday that Japan and South Korea must establish
"future-oriented ties" while trying to resolve differences over
their interpretation of Japan's colonial rule of the Korean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Japan's Diet (parliament), the visiting president
said: "The time has come for the two countries to face up to our
past and establish future-oriented relations."
</P>
<P>
"Japan needs true courage to squarely face the past...and the
Republic of Korea needs to correctly evaluate Japan's changing
attitude and find hope in future possibilities," the South Korean
leader said.
</P>
<P>
Kim described a joint declaration signed earlier in the day by
him and Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi as a milestone in
the two countries' efforts to overcome the differences.
</P>
<P>
The declaration put an end to a chapter of differences between
the two countries over their past, and would serve as the basis for
exploring a joint future of peace and prosperity, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, Obuchi expressed "deep remorse and heartfelt
apology" over the "pains and damage" Japan inflicted on the South
Korean people during its colonial rule from 1910 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
Kim said he planned to allow the introduction of Japanese
popular culture into his country in stages so as to boost the
friendly relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has banned popular Japanese culture from being
imported into the country since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference following the signing of the
declaration, Kim and Obuchi called for reconciliation between
the two countries and a departure from their strained relations
caused by Japan's colonization of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Kim arrived Wednesday on his first state visit to Japan since
his assumption of presidency in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
