<HEADLINE> Nigeria Signs 15 New Laws on Invesmtent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 8 (Xinhua) --Since Nigerian leader Abdulsalami
Abubakar took power in June this year, he has signed 15 new decrees
to encourage private and foreign investment in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
According to details released by the Justice Ministry Tuesday,
the new laws repealed and amended legislations inhibiting
investments in petroleum, mining, steel, electrical power,
telecommunications and other sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
They also provide tax and tariff incentives to encourage
investment in certain sectors, including gas utilization.
</P>
<P>
The new laws are a fuifillment of the government's promise to
amend or repeal laws inhibiting investment, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In its bid to attract investment, the Nigerian government has
started steps to privatize key public enterprises, including the
National Telecommunications, fertilizer and electrical power
companies, as well as major steel, paper and vehicle assembly
plants. 
