<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Justice Department Sues Visa, MasterCard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Justice Department
Wednesday sued Visa and MasterCard, the nation's biggest credit
card networks, accusing them of stifling competition.
</P>
<P>
Visa and MasterCard, with 50 percent and 25 percent of the
market respectively, "really don't compete with each other,
because they are both controlled by the same banks," said
Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein, who heads the Justice
Department's antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
In its lawsuit filed in the federal court in New York City, the
department also charged that Visa and MasterCard had adopted rules
that prohibited their member banks from offering the credit cards
of their rivals, such as American Express and Discover which have
a market share of only 18.4 percent and 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
A Visa bylaw adopted in the United States in 1991 banned Visa
members from offering the cards of American Express, Dean Witter,
Discover or other brands deemed competitive. MasterCard adopted
similar rules in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department asked the court to remove the
exclusionary rules from the networks' bylaws and to require that
banks governing an association be dedicated to one particular
network.
</P>
<P>
Both Visa and MasterCard denied the allegations, insisting that
their industry is among the nation's most competitive.
</P>
<P>
The case could have major consequences on the industry and the
antitrust law, experts say, noting that it could ease Visa and
MasterCard's powerful grip on the market and lead to greater
competition in the business as well as more cards and lower fees
for consumers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
