<HEADLINE> U.S. College Education Costs More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A survey released Wednesday
showed a four-percent rise in U.S. college expenses, one percent
lower than that for last year, but a ticket to a higher education
still cost 50 percent more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the College Board which represents
colleges, universities and educational associations, said the four
percent average growth rate was equivalent to a 132-U.S.-dollar
increase in tuition and fees at public four-year institutions
which average 3,243 U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
For private four-year colleges, average tuition and fees rose
723 U.S. dollars, up 5 percent to 14,508 U.S. dollars, according to
the survey of 3,000 U.S. public and private institutions.
</P>
<P>
"The share of family income required to pay college expenses has
increased for all families in the 1980s and 1990s, but it has gone up
the most for those at the low end of the economic scale," said
Lawrence Gladieus, an analyst with the College Board.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that attending a public four-year college or
university cost 62 percent of a low-income family's earnings and
17 percent of a middle-income family's earnings last year, the
latest year for which data were available.
</P>
<P>
Sending a child to a private institution would have consumed
162 percent of the earnings of a low-income family, compared with
44 percent of those of a middle-income family and 4 percent of
those of a high-income family, the survey added.
</P>
<P>
College Board President Donald Stewart urged families to begin
saving early for college.
</P>
<P>
Tuition and fees grew by an average of five percent last year
and six percent each of the three years before that. As a result
of an earlier round of double-digit growth, tuition at public
four-year institutions over the last decade has risen 50 percent,
adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
Family income during the same period rose only 1.5 percent, also
adjusted for inflation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
