<HEADLINE>   Duma Cancels Meeting With NATO Envoys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian State Duma (lower house
of parliament) Chairman Gennady Seleznyov Thursday announced the
scheduled Thursday's meeting in Duma with representatives of the
embassies of the NATO member-states in Moscow is called off.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, the planned meeting at
the lower house on Wednesday was to focus on the developments
of Kosovo and possible NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov, who is expected to attend the meeting, did not
explain the reason for the cancellation. However, according to
chairman of the State Duma International Affairs Committee
Vladimir Lukin, the embassies would most likely send "second
person" to such meetings.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and his Italian counterpart Romano Prodi held a second
telephone conversation on Kosovo Wednesday evening in two
days. They exchanged opinions on the prerequisites for the
settlement of the situation in Kosovo by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Prodi praised the efforts made by Russia,
adding that the world community expects Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic "to take additional steps to fully normalize
the situation."
</P>
<P>
Primakov stressed that as NATO continues threatening to take
military action in the Balkans, a meeting of the contact group
must be called immediately. 
</P>
