<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Urged to Ratify U.N. Biodiversity Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations official has
urged Thailand to ratify the Convention on Biodiversity so as to
share benefits of biological resources with technically-advanced
countries.
</P>
<P>
Thailand would also become a "financial magnet" and enjoy
technology transfer once it ratifies the convention, Daniel Navid,
a senior fellow of the U.N. Institute for Training and Research,
said in a statement available here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged environmentalists' fear about foreign
exploitation of the country's resources due to the absence of laws
governing the use of bio-resources, but said Thailand could set up
its own rules to control foreign companies utilizing its
resources.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Thailand has more than sophisticated laws
controlling usage of its resources. You shouldn't wait any longer
because you will miss an opportunity to receive financial aid. No
country has waited until they get their laws perfected," Navid
said.
</P>
<P>
"The convention is just a framework that can be very helpful to
Thailand ... to get support and technology," said Navid, who had
worked with the Thai government on conservation and biodiversity
in 1978 and 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the U.S. Information Service, Navid came here to
explain the impacts of the convention on Thailand.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 countries have already ratified the convention.
Among those which have yet to ratify it are Thailand and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists in Thailand oppose its ratification on
grounds that the country did not yet have necessary laws or
mechanisms to protect its biological resources against
exploitation by multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
They cautioned the Thai government not to be lured by promises
of influxes of financial aid and technology to support
ratification, but to consider its impacts on the country's
biological resources.
</P>
<P>
Navid said the challenge for Thailand in conservation is not
the lack of laws but law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington would ratify the convention in the future.
But he stressed that the U.S. move should not be used as a
yardstick to push Thailand to follow suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
