weaker at 2503.3, at the lower end of the day's trading range.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, the Nikkei Thursday shed 800 points to 13026 as a
strengthened yen raised concerns over Japanese exports.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index dipped 75.9 points to 4345.9 while the
all resources index slipped 3.2 points to 1027.3.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector continued its volatile week with the index
losing 91.8 points to 5235.1.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank dropped 50 cents to 19.35 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia fell 30 cents to 19.00
Australian dollars and Westpac bank descended 33.7 cents to 8.543
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank bucked the trend, adding 16 cents to 8.88 Australian
dollars.  In the diversified miners, BHP dipped 9.1 cents to
12.35 Australian dollars, Rio Tinto fell 38 cents to 19.01
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tne bright spot was the gold sector with the index adding 3.77
percent, or 45.9 points, to 1262.4 while the gold bullion closed
in Sydney Thursday at 301.60 U.S. dollars an ounce, up 3.55 U.S.
dollars from Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 295.45 million shares worth 561.76
million U.S. dollars with 470 rises, 549 falls and 339 steady
trades. 
