<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Lauds Egypt's Mediation in Ankara-Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Minister of Manpower Ali Al
Khalil Thursday praised Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
endeavors to put an end to the Syrian-Turkish crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made a several-hour visit to Turkey and Syria Tuesday
in his bid to contain the escalating tensions between the Mideast
neighbors from developing into armed conflicts. He has offered the
two countries a set of proposals to start a direct dialog for an
immediate solution.
</P>
<P>
"Mubarak presented Syria's viewpoint to the Turkish government,
not only as the president of Egypt, the largest Arab country, but
as the representative of the Arab nation," Khalil told the
Egyptian Voice of Arabs radio broadcast.
</P>
<P>
"He is there to tell the Turks: `we are keen on a good
relationship and good neighborliness with you,'" Khalil said in an
interview over telephone.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian minister said Damascus has not set any terms to
resolve this crisis, but at the same time it will not accept any
warnings or threats.
</P>
<P>
He was possibly referring to the Turkish government's decision
to give the Syrian government 45 days to "halt its support of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party," according to the Middle East
News Agency, quoting well-informed sources saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish cabinet, at a meeting Wednesday, agreed that if
Syria continues to maintain its position, Turkey will suspend
diplomatic action and adopt the measures it sees necessary.
</P>
<P>
During the 45-day leeway, Turkey will intensify diplomatic
action on the global arena, including visits by Turkish ministers
abroad to muster the largest possible support for its position.
</P>
<P>
He said Syria's strategy has always been dialog and he saw no
justification for the escalation of differences.
</P>
<P>
"Dialog has always been the tool of communication between
Turkey and Syria," he said, expressing belief that an Israeli
scheme was behind the current Ankara-Damascus crisis to drive a
wedge among Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
Strained ties between Mideast neighbors Syria and Turkey have
deteriorated in recent weeks with Syria bridling at Turkey's
growing military links with Israel and Turkey threatening Damascus
for allegedly aiding Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in
southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing Egyptian efforts reportedly aim at arranging a
meeting between the foreign ministers of Turkey and Syria and
opening the road for the resumption of their joint committee
meetings in a bid to contain the mounting tension between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Both sides appear to have pulled back from the brink in recent
days with separate announcements they sought diplomatic means to
resolve the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
