<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Continues to Rise on Stronger Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar rocketed
one and a half U.S. cents higher Thursday and traded above 62 U.S.
cents for the first time since July, buoyed by a rising Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed Thursday at 61.53 U.S. cents, up
from Wednesday's close of 60.58 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
It reached a high of 62.20 U.S. cents during Thursday's trade,
and dipped to a low of 61.25 U.S. cents while the consolidation
continued.
</P>
<P>
Scott Young, senior foreign exchange dealer at Arab Bank, said
that some profit taking took place Thursday afternoon, although
the local currency remained well bid.
</P>
<P>
He said the Australian dollar would continue to follow the
movements of the Japanese yen, and did not think it would fall
below 61.00 U.S. cents in overnight trade.
</P>
<P>
"It depends on how far the yen goes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Suggestions that Japan was on the verge of passing its bank
reforms had swayed in the yen's favor, despite the Japanese
government cutting its forecast for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Comments Wednesday night by U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan also led investors to turn away from the Greenback and
buy yen. His comments were interpreted as offering the possibility
of further interest rate cuts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 75.31 Japanese yen from 77.97
yen, and 0.9890 German marks from 0.9865 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
