<HEADLINE> Arafat Leaves Cairo for Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
left here Thursday morning for Moscow to seek a role by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin in pushing forward the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ambassador to Egypt, who saw Arafat off at the
airport, said the Palestinian leader will meet in Moscow with the
Russian president, premier and foreign minister to exchange views
on the developments of the peace march.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss coordinating stances regarding steps to
be taken in the coming phase to propel the peace march in the
Middle East, he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat flew to Cairo Wednesday night for talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak right after his meetings with Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
After a lengthy meeting with Netanyahu and Arafat, Albright
Wednesday announced that "significant and substantial progress has
been made" in the talks, and an October 15 summit would be held in
Washington to nail down an agreement on Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Albright flew to the region to narrow differences between the
two sides on a U.S. proposal on a 13 percent Israeli pullback in
exchange for Palestinian crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Russia are the co-sponsors of the 1991 Madrid
Conference which laid down the cornerstone of the Mideast
peace-making process, but Russia has lowered its profile since.
</P>
</TEXT>
