<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Million Chinese Suffer Hypertension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Some 100 million Chinese
citizens suffer from hypertension and the figure is expected to
climb due to a number of factors, including the rapidly aging
population, according to the Ministry of Health (MOH).
</P>
<P>
A recent national survey revealed the number of Chinese
hypertension patients swells by three million annually, with the
disorder causing 1.5 million strokes and 750,000 cases of coronary
heart disease each year, according to MOH Vice Minister Yin Dakui.
</P>
<P>
"The aforementioned diseases have emerged as the No.1 cause of
death in China and are responsible for 40 percent of
illness-related fatalities," said Yin. He made the comments
earlier today in a meeting marking the first "National
Hypertension Day".
</P>
<P>
Health departments nationwide have organized various activities
to disseminate information on hypertension. "We must enhance
public awareness in order to achieve effective prevention and
controls," according to the MOH official.
</P>
<P>
Yin pointed that high blood pressure is not only health
threatening, but also overburdens sufferers with substantial
medical costs.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the rising susceptibility of Chinese to the
disease to improper lifestyles and dramatic social changes. They
point to specific causes such as obesity, high levels of
cholesterol in blood, an excessive intake of salt, smoking, mental
fatigue and the lack of physical exercises.
</P>
<P>
"An urgent nationwide prevention campaign must be launched to
introduce measures needed to effectively control 75 percent of
hypertension cases and related complications," according to
Professor Liu Lisheng, chairwoman of the Chinese Hypertension
League.
</P>
<P>
Some 21 Beijing hospitals joined today's activities by offering
free blood pressure checks.
</P>
<P>
The MOH recently received a grant of five million yuan from
Pfizer Pharmaceuticals Ltd, a joint venture between Pfizer
Inc. and the Dalian Pharmaceutical Plant, to fund hypertension
research and health education programs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
