<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Pledges to Accelerate Reform Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
pledged to accelerate its on-going reform process at an
appropriate pace with structural economic adjustments, media
reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and governor of the state bank Nguyen Tan
Dung made the pledge when addressing the opening session of the
53rd World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) annual
meeting in Washington Tuesday, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Dung said Vietnam has been suffering from the heavy impact of
the regional crisis and is also subject to serious consequences of
natural calamities.
</P>
<P>
He said Vietnam's gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate is
estimated at 6 percent in 1998, the lowest level in the last seven
years.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports failed to increase substantially while
foreign direct investments were only 60 percent of the 1997 level.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam was also facing growing unemployment and difficulties
in balancing payment.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Vietnam is watching closely the evolution of
the crisis and is drawing valuable lessons from the crisis
countries," Dung said.
</P>
<P>
Being a poor and least developed country, Vietnam's recent
achievements gained by mobilizing domestic resources and limited
assistance from donors and foreign investors have not been
sufficient to prevent the decline in economic growth and reduce
the adverse impact of the regional crisis, said Dung.
</P>
<P>
He said Vietnam's government is committed to accelerating the
reform process at an appropriate pace with structural economic
adjustment so that all domestic resources can be maximized, the
impact of the crisis be minimized and socio-economic stability and
development be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Dung requested the IMF and the World Bank to increase
concessional funding and to provide technical assistance to
Vietnam "in a more timely and more practical fashion in
implementing economic reform and structural adjustment."
</P>
<P>
He added that Vietnam wishes to reach an agreement on
structural adjustment credit and an enhanced structural adjustment
facility program as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
