<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Online Survey Shows Y2K Generating Worries Among Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Year 2000 computer problem
is generating serious worries even among well-educated Americans,
according to an online survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A majority of the 6,300 respondents are worried that the
millennium bug will negatively affect the U.S. stock market and
plan to prepare themselves and their families in some way.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by Ziff-Davis (ZD), an integrated
media and marketing company focusing on computing and Internet, in
partnership with the professional Harris Poll. Based on the
survey's demographics, ZD's online service ZDNet said, the
respondents are a well-educated, well-to-do group, many of whom
work in the information technology field.
</P>
<P>
84 percent of the respondents claim at least a "good" or
"complete" understanding of Y2K. While few foresee a doomsday
scenario, 61 percent anticipate at least "somewhat serious"
effects on them or their families. But only 25 percent anticipate
a Y2K-related domestic recession.
</P>
<P>
Presumably out of the concerns, nearly four-fifth of the
respondents plan to do some preparations, such as stocking up on
extra food, fuel, batteries and candles. More than 60 percent have
considered avoiding air travel and withdrawing money from a
bank. A quarter of them have thought about taking nearly all of
their money out from the banks.
</P>
<P>
ZDNet said as the respondents were not randomly selected, the
poll was not a scientific one and therefore the results cannot be
projected to a larger population of the general public or Internet
users.
</P>
<P>
There are also "good news", the amused ZDNet editors said many
of the respondents expressed confidence that they and their
employers will have the bug licked by the day of reckoning. In
fact, three-quarters report that their employer has taken steps to
prepare for Y2K, while 85 percent believe their firms will achieve
their compliance goals in time for 2000.
</P>
<P>
As for the responsibility, only a slight majority of the
respondents think the government ought to take a stronger role to
addressing the issue. But if something goes wrong, Uncle Sam
wouldn't bear the brunt of the blame. Nearly three-fifths said
they would mostly hold business leaders and information technology
professionals responsible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
