<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Financial Crisis And Traditional Asian Thought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- One lesson of the Asian
financial crisis is that the affected nations have copied too
much from the West while ignoring their own valuable traditional
thought, according to scholars attending an ongoing seminar
here.
</P>
<P>
The 2nd International Symposium on Oriental Thought, which
began on Tuesday and will end on Friday, attracted more than
100 scholars and specialists from China, the Republic of Korea,
Japan, Singapore, and China's Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Huang Fanzhang, a researcher with the Macro-Economics Research
Institute under the State Development Planning Commission, said in
a paper presented to the seminar that the problems of East Asian
economies, which resulted in the current crisis, were caused by
the region's deviation from traditional thought.
</P>
<P>
This traditional thought, according to some participants,
embraces Confucianism, Taoism, Buddhism and Islam, as well as
Shintoism in Japan.
</P>
<P>
"The 'magic' economic boom of the last 30 years in East Asia
was a result of Oriental traditional thought," said Huang, also a
professor at Beijing's People's University. "The so-called 'East
Asia Economic Model,' characterized by government dominance, a
high savings rate and an export-oriented economy, was nurtured by
traditional thought."
</P>
<P>
He defended the Asian model as not the major cause of the turmoil,
saying that what is responsible is the abuse of the model.
</P>
<P>
"The Asia financial turmoil cannot overshadow the brightness of
Oriental culture," he said.
</P>
<P>
Huang's ideas were echoed by another Chinese scholar, Wang Zhan,
director of the Development Research Center of the Shanghai
Municipal Government. He said Oriental nations should mainly
look to traditional thought as they try to find their way in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
"Western civilization does not deserve to be the universal
growth model," said the well-known economist. "Instead, the
essence of Oriental culture, which played a pivotal role in the
fast-growing Asian nations, should be explored."
</P>
<P>
Wang listed frugality, family ethics, individual relationships,
education and harmonious co-existence with nature as the key
points to be explored.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that Asian nations discard the negative
elements of the Oriental culture, and learn from the West in a
dynamic and reasonable way.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuhashi Tadahiro, a commentator with the Hihon Keizai Shimbun
(Japan Economic Journal), warned that Asian nations which want to
catch up with the West should not copy the "dangerous" American
growth model.
</P>
<P>
"Characterized by high consumption of natural resources and
high consumption, the American style has caused evident damage to
the global environment," he said. "(They) should look to their
good traditional habits such as frugality, and achieve a growth
style where man and nature develop in a harmonious relationship."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Members of Banned Political Party Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's State Security Court has
convicted five members of a banned political party for membership
in illegal group, the semi-official Jordan Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The five were given sentences ranging from six to 18 months,
the paper quoted an unnamed source as saying.
</P>
<P>
They were among the 20 members of the Al Tahrir (liberation)
Party arrested last month when they distributed leaflets in some
cities, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Other detainees will stand trial later this month, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Al Tahrir Party, established in Palestine, has been banned
for years and it is known as the only officially-announced
underground opposition party by Jordanian government.
</P>
<P>
The party insists on Islamic ideology and wants Jordan to
have Islamic law that is based on the Koran.
</P>
<P>
Jordan allows the existence of opposition parties, but they
must officially register and are not allowed to conduct
underground activities.
</P>
<P>
Registered opposition parties have been active in the kingdom
and usually hold seats in the Lower House of Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
