<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Confident of Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada expressed here Thursday his confidence of the recovery of
the country's economy from the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a speech on government programs during the first 100 days of
his administration, Estrada said that recent economic and
financial developments have given "us confidence that we can
overcome this crisis."
</P>
<P>
During the first eight months of this year, the Philippines'
inflation averaged at 8.4 percent. Estrada said the rate is one of
the lowest in the region and remains within the government's
single-digit inflation target of 9.25-9.75 percent for the whole
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exports grew by 18.8 percent for the first half of
this year, higher than most countries in the region, and the
government's fiscal deficit dropped from 93 billion pesos (about
2.1 billion U.S. dollars) to 40 billion pesos (909 million
dollars) due to various fiscal disciplines taken by the
government.
</P>
<P>
During the first 100 days of Estrada's governance, the
government also gave top priority to the modernization of
agriculture, the revival of industry, poverty reduction, the
delivery of housing, employment, education, health and social
services and the peace talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the government's efforts, the Philippines is the
only one among its Asian neighbors that is projected to show
positive economic growth this year.
</P>
<P>
"The country remains one of the few promising economies in a
region where many others are expected to go into recession,"
Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
He added that this confidence was affirmed by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
IMF managing director Michel Camdessus said earlier that the
Philippines is "the least affected" by the Asian financial crisis
and might be the first nation to get out of the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
