<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Makes World "Global Village" for Tibetans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey shows that 94
percent of Tibetan households now have TV sets, and TV relay
stations cover all the villages and towns in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
In major cities and towns such as Lhasa, Nagqu, Xigaze and
Shiquanhe, more than 20 local and satellite channels are
available, including broadcasts in Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
A soccer fan named Dogyal said he was able to enjoy all the
matches during the '98 World Cup via live telecasts from China
Central Television (CCTV).
</P>
<P>
Pubu Drolmar, a resident of Bargor Street, put the TV set in
front of her niche and said her favorite program is a TV series
called "East Journey of Panchen," but she felt a little sad that
there was no version in Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey of Bargor Street, 80 percent of the
residents there watch the Tibetan-language programs on the CCTV
News and local news everyday.
</P>
<P>
Drashi Drolmar, a local official, said that she was moved to
tears and donated 300 yuan to the flood-hit areas after watching
news of the flood-fighting campaigns on TV.
</P>
<P>
Even in the pastoral areas, which now have electricity and
satellite relay facilities, watching TV has become the most
popular entertainment for Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Dolungdeqen County at first disliked advertisements
on TV, but later changed their attitude. Thanks to ads, they have
cooperated with companies in other provinces to set up many
township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Tibetans say airplanes and telephones have shortened the
distance between Tibet and the rest of the world, but it is TV
that really has made the world a "global village" for
them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
