<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guest Workers Given a Month to Legalize Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian government has decided
to give illegal foreign workers a month to legalize their status,
the Jordan Times newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting an official the paper said a total of 17 offices across
the country will keep open for the guest workers to apply for work
permits until the beginning of next month.
</P>
<P>
By then, those who can not legalize their status will be
deported according to relevant laws and regulations, said Bahjat
Quteishat, head of the Labor and Employment Department of the
Ministry of Labor.
</P>
<P>
The number of applicants has increased sharply since the
government declared at the end of last month to strictly regulate
the foreign labor market.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a campaign launched by the government on
September 30 to curb employment of non-Jordanians and return job
chances to unemployed Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
In the past days, police have rounded up hundreds of Asian
workers. Those with valid work permits will be allowed to stay,
while those without will be fined some 140 U.S. dollars and be
deported at employers' expense.
</P>
<P>
Official figures put foreign workers living in Jordan between
300,000 to 500,000, most of whom are are Egyptians, Syrians and
Iraqis. Only 40 percent of them hold valid work permits.
</P>
<P>
They are widely believed to have grabbed job opportunities from
Jordanians. Employers like to hire these people because they can
pay less and do not have to undertake their insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
