<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddhist Relics Discovered in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Construction workers in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province discovered sariras--a combination of bone
ashes of eminent Buddhist monks-- in a 1,400-year-old tower as
they were attempting to move the tower to a location 3 kilometers
away.
</P>
<P>
The 30-meter-high tower, located in southern Zhouzhi County and
on the State's protected list, was built in 601 by Yang Jian, an
emperor of the Sui Dynasty (581-618).
</P>
<P>
In order to make way for a water project, the local government
decided to move the tower, and with the approval of the State
Council the task began in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
On September 17, while working on the second floor of the
tower, construction workers dug a small bronze coffin out of a pit
which was covered by two large bricks.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists in the province hurried to the site and opened
the coffin which was wrapped with paper and silk. The coffin is
11.9 cm long, 7.6 cm wide and 10.5 cm high, and contained a glazed
white bottle in which were found bean-sized sariras, one white and
two yellow.
</P>
<P>
Archeologiests said there might be another chamber under the
tower as they heard a hollow sound below as they rapped on the
tower's base, and further discoveries are possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
