<HEADLINE> 7 Dead in PNG Highland Landslide: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Seven people died Tuesday when
a landslide swept away two homes in a remote village in the
highlands of Papua New Guinea (PNG), the Australian Associated
Press (AAP) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A girl aged eight or nine escaped Tuesday's landslide
uninjured, said Wakaf Macksaen, deputy provincial administrator of
Enga province.
</P>
<P>
He said the landslide occurred around 4:00 a.m. Tuesday,
instead of last Friday as reported earlier, in an isolated area
southeast of the Maramuni Station in the north of Enga province,
following heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
Macksaen, who visited the site of the landslide at Pafalangus
village earlier Thursday, said media reports that up to 140 people
in a church congregation may have perished in a landslide last
Friday were "all wrong."
</P>
<P>
PNG's national newspaper National Thursday reported that over
100 people were feared to have been buried alive in a landslide
that struck a church congregation in the nation's remote Maramuni
area of Enga province last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Macksaen said the landslide carried away two houses made of
flimsy bush materials nestled in a valley surrounded by steep
mountains.
</P>
<P>
"There were a total of eight people in the houses. One escaped,
the others were carried away," Macksaen told AAP.
</P>
<P>
Macksaen said the seven dead included five men and two women,
and three or four of the bodies had been recovered from the mud
and debris.
</P>
<P>
The eight people in the two destroyed houses had probably been
asleep at the time the landslide occurred.
</P>
<P>
The young girl who survived was believed to be staying with her
relatives.
</P>
<P>
Macksaen said the area around Maramuni was very unstable and
landslides occurred regularly.
</P>
<P>
A landslide in the area in 1960 killed 60 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
