<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Finds Way for One-Dose Cure of Genetic Disorders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand scientists have
found a way to treat genetic disorders that promises a one-dose
cure for diseases such as stomach cancer and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
According to a report recently published in the New Zealand
Herald, an Auckland-based newspaper, a group of scientists at the
Auckland School of Medicine have used a gene-therapy treatment
taken orally to cure the world's commonest genetic disorder,
lactose intolerance, in rats.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that within a decade a "dose" of the same gene
therapy will be used to combat inherited conditions in humans,
such as hemophilia, intestinal cancer, cystic fibrosis and
obesity, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It reported that molecular biologist Matthew During, head of
the group, cured lactose-intolerant rats by delivering a
lactose-digesting gene into the tissue that needed it.
</P>
<P>
He found that the rats could digest lactose after only one oral
dose of the missing genetic material.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Professor During as saying the breakthrough
cleared the way for a whole generation of new gene-therapy drugs.
</P>
<P>
Gene therapy is a method of treating diseases caused by genetic
 abnormalities by replacing the defective gene with a corrected
one.
</P>
<P>
Problems have always existed with targeting the specific tissue
 containing the faulty gene and keeping the corrected gene
functioning long term.
</P>
<P>
The group of scientists inserted the missing gene
b-galactosidase, which produces the lactose-digesting enzyme,
into rats' intestines.
</P>
<P>
The gene was incorporated into cells lining the rats'
gastrointestinal tract, allowing them to metabolize lactose.
</P>
<P>
Six months later the rats remain tolerant to lactose,
suggesting that a one-dose pill could be used to treat human
genetic diseases.
</P>
<P>
"This research brings gene therapy one step closer to the
clinic," Professor During said.
</P>
<P>
"Delivery of the missing gene has always been the problem, but
this research makes it feasible to give gene-therapy orally in
the form of a pill," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   World's Top 20 Men to Play Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The world's top 20 ranked men
tennis players will compete in January's Australian Open in
Melbourne while 18 of the top 20 women have also confirmed their
entries, Tennis Australia (TA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Prize money has been increased to 11.75 million dollars (7.05
million U.S. dollars), 17.5 percent more than last year, TA
president Geoff Pollard said.
</P>
<P>
Of the world's top 20 women, only Jana Novotna of Czech
Republic and Nathalie Tauziat of France are unlikely to attend
the tournament, which runs from January 18 to 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
