<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Chinese Women Accept Contraception </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 8 (Xinhua) -- It has become common in rural
Dalian in northeast China's Liaoning Province to find women who
choose suitable methods of contraception for the purpose of birth
control.
</P>
<P>
Xu Zhijuan of Luhai Village in the city's Jinzhou District has
been using condoms since she gave birth to two girls, while Zhang
Guixiang of the same village decided to use an intrauterine device
after she had a boy.
</P>
<P>
In the fishing village, all the 33 women of childbearing age
have chosen one method of contraception or another.
</P>
<P>
There are several ways to control birth such as ligature,
hypodermic implantation, condoms and oral contraceptives. However,
rural women used to have only two choices, ligature or an
intrauterine device, because of the limited medical facilities in
the countryside.
</P>
<P>
As one of ten pilot cities in China promoting contraception in
rural areas, Dalian launched five years ago a program to encourage
rural women to choose suitable methods for themselves.
</P>
<P>
The local government has also helped set up 98 family planning
clinics in 130 towns offering women services such as physical
examinations and contraception consultations.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the old idea among rural people that "more children
means greater fortune" is rapidly disappearing.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-year-old Hong Xiumei chose to use condoms after she had
a girl, though she can have another child according to State
policy.
</P>
<P>
Hong said she now can provide more love and care for her only
daughter and hopes the child will eventually attend college, a
dream of her own which did not come true because her parents had
too many children to take care of with low income.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Village Leaders Arrested for Illegal Logging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Three of 12 village leaders
recently arrested for illegal logging in east China's Shandong
Province have been sentenced to prison, and the remaining
officials were subject to disciplinary sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The arrests saved state assets of well over 900,000 yuan
(108,433 US dollars), according to the Shandong Forestry Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show an increase in cases of illegal logging in the
province in the first half of the year, with the 900 related cases
doubling the number for the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that forest rangers throughout the
province will use the local 110 police hot line as a means of
strengthening enforcement operations. 
</P>
