<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Study: High Tech Moves Beyond Silicon Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 7 (Xinhua) -- A study released Wednesday
said that high technology was increasingly creating jobs in
major Californian metropolitan areas other than San Jose in the
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the American Electronics Association,
said that the San Jose metropolitan area employed 221,000 high
technology workers, representing nearly a third of all the 724,000
technology jobs in the state of California in 1996, with an
average annual wage of 72,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The second largest metropolitan area in terms of employment was
Los Angeles, with 147,000 jobs and an annual wage of 51,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sacramento, Fresno, Vallejo-Napa and San Francisco were also
emerging as high-tech metropolitan zones, where high tech
employment grew by 56 percent, 54 percent, 46 percent and 37
percent respectively in the 1990-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
"Increasingly, high tech is a statewide phenomenon as other
California cities become more attractive because of their
competitive cost of living, skilled labor force and quality of
life," said Joseph Dooling, a senior vice president of the
American Electronics Association, an industrial trade group, in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The above employment and salary data, which combined statistics
from the U.S. census bureau, were only available through 1996. The
wage data, said the study, has likely increased over the past two
years, especially in Silicon Valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
