<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Prospers from Foreign Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Sister-city ties with the
outside world has helped east China's Jiangsu Province realize a
foreign trade volume of 1.68 billion US dollars over the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu is home to more than 1,000 foreign-funded enterprises
established as a result of the outside ties.
</P>
<P>
The province leads the nation in keeping the ties with 102
foreign cities.
</P>
<P>
The wide-ranging ties involve science, education, culture,
sports and public health. Related ties have led to exchanges
involving well over 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Some 270 foreign experts, teachers and professors have worked
in the province, with more than 1,500 local residents travelling
abroad to conduct research or receive further training.
</P>
<P>
Such ties began to be estabished in 1978 when the provincial
capital of Nanjing became friendship city with Nagoya, Japan, with
the approval of late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu currently has such ties in 29 countries and regions in
Asia, Australia, the Americas and Europe.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition was inaugurated in Nanjing Wednesday to display
achievements made in the regard over the past 20-odd years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Records Big Trade Surplus in 1st 8 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a
significant trade surplus in the first eight months this year as a
result of increase in exports and decline in imports.
</P>
<P>
The surplus during the period under review amounted to 32.4
billion ringgit (about 8.526 billion U.S. dollars) in contrast to
a deficit of 2.5 billion ringgit (about 657.894 million U.S.
dollars) in the corresponding period last year, according to
figures released by the Statistics Department Thursday.
</P>
<P>
For the January-August 1998 period, exports rose strongly by
38.6 percent to 187.1 billion ringgit (about 49.236 billion U.S.
dollars), while imports increased by 12.5 percent to 154.6 billion
ringgit (about 40.684 billion U.S. dollars), in comparison with
those for the corresponding period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The department said that electrical and electronic products,
Malaysia's largest export earner, netted receipts amounting to
51.8 percent of the total export earnings in January-August 1998
period, recording a 42.9 percent increase over the corresponding
period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Palm oil and palm-based products, the second largest export
earner of the country, accounted for 7.8 percent of total exports
during the first eight months of 1998, recording a 71.7 percent
growth over that recorded in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Other major export earners include liquefied natural gas (LNG),
which accounted for 2.9 percent of total exports and increased by
26.1 percent, and crude petroleum which accounted for 2.7 percent
of total exports and increased by 20.6 percent in the period under
review compared with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On imports, the department said the major categories of imports
by end-use for the period under review were intermediate goods
amounting to 69.9 percent of total imports, capital goods 16.8
percent and consumption goods 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the January-August 1998 period, Malaysia's top three
trading partners continued to be Japan, the United States and
Singapore, which collectively accounted for 51.5 percent of the
country's total trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
