<HEADLINE> Worldwide Server Revenues Decline in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide server revenues
approached 9.9 billion U.S. dollars in the second quarter, down
11.2 percent from the same period a year ago, according to a
report released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
California-based market analysis firm Dataquest reported that
in the second quarter, server revenue in the Asia-Pacific region
(excluding Japan with a 31.6 percent drop) declined 34 percent,
compared with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Revenue declines were also reported in other two major markets
-- the United States, 6 percent, and Canada, 27.8 percent. With
3.6 billion dollars in server revenue and a moderate increase of
7.7 percent, western Europe was the only market experiencing a
positive growth.
</P>
<P>
Last week another U.S. market analysis firm, International Data
Corporation (IDC), reported that worldwide PC server shipments in
the second quarter dropped to just over 487,800 units,
representing a negative 1 percent sequential growth.
</P>
<P>
According to IDC analysis, turmoil in Japan played a major role
in the worldwide PC server shipment decline. The overall downturn
was also due to increased inventory in the United States, modest
growth in Europe and a slowdown in high-end PC server sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
