<HEADLINE> 32 Killed, 70 Feared to Have Been Killed in PNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-two people were killed
and over 70 others are feared to have been buried alive in a huge
landslide that took place last Friday in Papua New Guinea (PNG),
the nation's national newspaper National reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper's electronic edition available on
the Internet, a landslide struck a church congregation in Papua
New Guinea's (PNG)'s remote Maramuni area of Enga province last
Friday during the current rainy season.
</P>
<P>
There is no road and telephone links in the remote area of
Maramuni.
</P>
<P>
The paper said a nine-year-old girl, Yutia Lusate, was the sole
survivor of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
A total of eight bodies had been found under muddy soil and
were buried in a mass grave, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Senior Maramuni Councillor Reuben Kini said the victims were
sleeping after attending a big prayer session called "Holy Spirit
Movement" when the disaster happened.
</P>
<P>
He said the nine-year-old girl managed to escape and reported
the landslide disaster to nearby people.
</P>
<P>
The death toll could rise to as high as 140, he said.
</P>
<P>
PNG's National Disaster and Emergency Services office said it
had received reports of the disaster Saturday and had yet to
confirm the reports.
</P>
<P>
A landslide in the area in 1960 killed 60 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
