<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo, Seoul Agree to Establish New Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi and visiting South Korean President Kim Dae Jung agreed
Thursday to establish a new Japan-South Korea partnership toward
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was contained in a joint declaration and a
supplementary action plan the two leaders signed after their
two-hour meeting at the Akasaka State Guest House on the second
day of Kim's four-day state visit.
</P>
<P>
"The two leaders agreed on the importance of developing ties
based on trust and mutual understanding while facing outright the
history between the two nations in order to build a firm friendly
relationship in the 21st century," the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi expressed "deep remorse and heartfelt apology" over the
"pains and damages" Japan inflicted on the South Korean people
during Japan's 1910-1945 colonial rule of the Korean Peninsula,
said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
It said Kim appreciated Obuchi's remarks, and called for
"mutual efforts to develop future-oriented relations while
overcoming the tragic history between the two nations."
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to step up bilateral dialogue,
including holding a summit at least once a year, to build
"balanced high-level cooperative" ties in a wide range of areas
from cultural exchanges to economic and security matters.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi pledged to continue supporting South Korea's efforts to
overcome its financial crisis, and the two leaders agreed to
promote "policy coordination" further in bilateral and
multilateral economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Kim reiterated his policy of opening access to Japanese culture
in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Kim arrived here Wednesday on his first state visit to Japan
since taking office in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
