<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Likely to Ease Tech Import Regime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
likely to ease technology import regime and treat technology
acquired by Indian companies as capital, a government official
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Committee of Secretaries cleared an Industry
Ministry proposal to shift technology imports for projects
assessed and funded by financial institutions (FIs) to the
automatic approval list of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI). The
proposal seeks to remove restrictions on the quantum of lumpsum
payment, royalty and the phasing of installments for technology
imports.
</P>
<P>
The move will remove bottlenecks in technology imports allowing
companies to include them in project cost and raise loans from
banks and FIs.
</P>
<P>
At present, know-how and licence fees cannot be funded as part
of capital expenditure.
</P>
<P>
On its part, the Department of Science and Technology has
proposed an insurance cover against technology failure to
facilitate finances. According to the department, insurance cover
would go a long way in encouraging the industry to enhance
technology.
</P>
<P>
The move follows the realization of importance of allowing
Indian companies to bring in the latest technology and also be
able to finance its purchase to make them internationally
competitive, the official said.
</P>
<P>
India is poor in capital goods technology and has to depend on
the developed countries. Large projects like petro-chemical
plants, power units have a significant part of their project cost
as technology fee and related expenditure, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
