<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Prices Rise Sharply on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Prices of grain, soybean,
pork and beef rose sharply Wednesday on market rumors that Russia
needs donations of corn and wheat from the United States to make
up its crop production shortages, according to reports from
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, wheat for December delivery
rose by 11.75 cents to 2.95 U.S. dollars per bushel; December corn
rose by 7.75 cents to 2.18 dollars per bushel; and November
soybeans rose by 10.75 cents to 5.33 dollars a bushel.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Agriculture said Wednesday that Russia
had made no formal requests for food aid donations, but it had
made preliminary inquiries.
</P>
<P>
There have been rumors in the U.S. market that Russia was
seeking from the U.S. three million tons of wheat, 1.5 million
tons of corn, 500,000 tons of soybean meal and 100,000 tons of
pork.
</P>
<P>
A sharp drop in the U.S. dollar, particularly against the yen,
also supported grain prices. Market analysts say a weaker dollar
makes U.S. goods cheaper to purchase and could cause a flurry of
export demand if it remains low.
</P>
<P>
Pork futures also benefited from Russian talk on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, as some investors speculated that the
U.S. government could snap up as much as 100 million dollars worth
of pork to donate overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Province Anticipates Bumper Fruit Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi Province
anticipates a record fruit harvest for the year, with total output
projected at five million tons.
</P>
<P>
Sources indicated that the volume will account for close to 10
percent of the nation's total fruit output.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi, home of the famous Qin Dynasty (221-266 B.C.) terra
cotta warriors and horses, enjoys ideal conditions for apples,
pears, dates and kiwi.
</P>
<P>
Fruit growers have paid great attention to agrobiological
applications in recent years to increase production, including
grafting, efficient irrigation and the prevention of plant
diseases and insect infestations. Related efforts have yielded a
general improvement in fruit quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
