<HEADLINE> Poland to Seek Ways to Prevent Escalation of Kosovo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Poland is determined to find a
way to prevent the Kosovo conflict from escalating into an even
greater tragedy, Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski and Prime
Minister Jerzy Buzek said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Polish News Agency (PAP) said the Polish president met with
the prime minister to discuss the Balkan political and military
situation.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek,
also rotating president of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), discussed the organization's
political options to help resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Buzek told local reporters that Poland is ready
to take part in NATO's military action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Polish Defense Minister Janusz Onyszkiewicz said the air forces
from NATO member countries would spearhead the military
action. The North Atlantic Treaty Organization did not expect
Poland to send troops, though his country did participate in
NATO's decision, Onyszkiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if a new "cold war" would break out after Russia voiced
opposition against NATO's proposed air strikes against Yugoslavia,
the defense minister said the western countries would not allow
Russia to succeed.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Geremek said that the Yugoslav foreign
minister requested on Tuesday that OSCE send a mission to Kosovo
to talk with the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
He said he would not go to Belgrade, because he believes that
Belgrade lacks sincerity. Geremek said the world is not only
facing a potential military conflict, but a humanitarian
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE head said there is still a chance to avoid a military
conflict, which may be resolved during U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke's talks.  
</P>
