<HEADLINE> Flood Loss in Bangladesh Estimated at 4.3 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Planning Ministry's
preliminary estimate puts the total loss caused by the
two-month-long devastating flood at around 4.3 billion U.S.
dollars, The Financial Express reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The total loss would be around 10 percent of the GDP (gross
domestic product), the paper quoted State Minister for Planning
Mohiuddin Khan Alamgir as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's GDP size is around 43 billion dollars, according
to the revised national accounts.
</P>
<P>
The government has worked out short-term and long-term
rehabilitation programs of around 900 million dollars for the
current fiscal year starting from July 1998.
</P>
<P>
An aid of around 230 million dollars would be required to
implement the rehabilitation programs, he stated.
</P>
<P>
The local resource requirement for the rehabilitation programs
would be around 600 million dollars, of which about 304 million
dollars would be available from this year's annual development
program, while the mobilization of 289 million dollars would be
required, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far commitment from the development partners is around 200
million dollars both in cash and kind, which is much less than
what was expected, the report quoted sources in the Planning
Commission as saying.
</P>
<P>
Alamgir hoped that the response of the foreign development
partners would be better. Both the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank had fielded assessment teams to Bangladesh, and
after completion of their assessments, response from foreign
sources would be better, he added.
</P>
<P>
The immediate priority of the government is the agriculture
rehabilitation programs, he said, adding that the government has
decided to disburse loan amounting to 32.5 billion taka (about
691.5 million dollars), almost double the disbursement in the last
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The government has also allocated 500 million taka (about 10.6
million dollars) to support the marginal farmers, he stated.
</P>
<P>
On private sector industrial rehabilitation programs, the state
minister said the banks have been asked to meet the working
capital demand.
</P>
<P>
Under the rehabilitation programs, road communication received
the highest allocation of 13.75 billion taka (about 292.6 million
dollars), which is 32.22 percent of the total allocation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The local governments received the second highest allocation of
9.65 billion taka (about 205.3 million dollars) and the Water
Resources Ministry got the third highest allocation of 6.34
billion taka (about 134.9 million dollars), he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
