<HEADLINE> Myanmar Bans Certain Brands of Foreign Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar health authorities
have prohibited the application and sale of 13 brands of
unregistered eye drops imported from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Of the 13 brands of eye drops, eight are from India, two from
China and one each from Germany, Belgium and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Official paper The New Light of Myanmar Thursday quoted the
Ministry of Health as saying that the unregistered eye drops have
not been examined for their potency and quality and safety.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid danger, the sellers and users have been asked
to use the registered ones.
</P>
<P>
Recently, many people suffered from seasonal soar eye disease
in the country, widely using imported eye drops without knowing
whether they are registered or not.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, since August last year, the Myanmar authorities have
also banned 22 brands of Myanmar traditional drugs and 26 local
and foreign brands of purified bottled water for public
consumption in a crackdown on expired food and medicines as well
as unhygienic locally-produced preserves.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar enacted the National Food Law in March 1997 and formed
the special Food and Drug Authority in its bid to enable the
public to consume food of genuine quality, free from danger and
hygienic problems, and to control and regulate the production,
import, export, storage, distribution and sale of food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
