<HEADLINE> India Develops Green Technology for Textile Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Indian research organizations
have developed a green technology for the country's textile
industry and the new system is under trial.
</P>
<P>
The Mumbai-based Textile Research Association and the Petroleum
Conservation Research Association have worked out a new system to
check air pollution caused by the textile industry and a plant has
been set up to demonstrate the effectiveness of the device, the
Business Standard said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that such a system has been developed in
India. During printing of cotton fabrics, called pigment printing,
the kerosene used is retained in the cloth after the process is
over. The cloth is then dried on machine dryers which result in
vaporization of kerosene.
</P>
<P>
The new system can recapture and recycle the kerosene vapors
which can then be reused as fresh input. The new system can
recover about 80 percent of the vapors, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
