<HEADLINE> Tyson Petition Supreme Court to Keep Records Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson petitioned the
Nevada Supreme Court on Wednesday with an effort to keep
psychological test results known from the public.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's petition came after a lower court's refusal ruling on
Monday. He hope the Supreme Court can reconsider an order
allowing the records to be made public upon their release to the
Nevada Athletic Commission.
</P>
<P>
A team of psychiatrists examined Tyson for five days last
week, and worked out the documents.
</P>
<P>
Commission members decided on the September 19 hearing that
Tyson's fate would be determined by the results. If he passed the
tests, the former heavyweight champion would perhaps regain his
license.
</P>
<P>
Tyson lawyer Jim Jimmerson said it was clear the records
should be kept under wraps "when considering the harm likely to
be suffered by (Tyson). Clearly when balancing the public
curiosity in these records to Tyson's interest in maintaining
their confidentiality, the court could have reasonably found that
these sensitive records should be withheld from public
inspection," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jimmerson said that Dr. Ronald Schouten, who directed the
tests, agreed that the information should only go to the Athletic
Commission for its internal use.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer also pointed out that Tyson is in poor financial
shape and needs to box again to support himself and his family.
Tyson desperately needs money to pay off a 13 million lien to the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
Tyson faces an October 19 trial in Montgomery County despite
efforts by his attorneys to settle with the two men who were
beaten by Tyson in a traffic accident in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
