<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso has been re-elected for the period 1999-2000,
receiving more than half of all votes.
</P>
<P>
With 95.57 percent of the votes counted Wednesday, Cardoso had
received 52.88 percent of the votes, far ahead of his closest
rival, Luiz Inacio "Lula" da Silva, who took 31.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso's absolute majority means there will be no runoff in
the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
According to the Superior Electoral Tribunal, 12 presidential
candidates participated in Brazil's general elections, which
started on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ciro Gomes, Popular Socialist Party's candidate, received 11.05
percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
But Cardoso's Social Democratic Party of Brazil registered some
losses in gubernatorial elections and a second round of voting
will be held on October 25 to elect governors.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, president Cardoso spoke publicly to the
press for the first time since the general elections to thank the
people for their support. He pledged to carry out his duties
during his second term. 
