<HEADLINE> Venezuela, Suriname Sign Fishing Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela and Suriname signed an
agreement on Wednesday to conserve and exploit marine life in the
sea, and to enhance water rights and fishing agreements between
their two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by the foreign ministers of Venezuela
and Suriname, Miguel Angel Burelli Rivas and Errol Snijders, at
the Venezuelan Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"With the subscription of this juridical instrument, a
negotiation which started in 1993 came to an end," the Venezuelan
Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations had given a decisive impetus to the active
participation of the fishing sectors, the statement added. The
new agreement will replace the one signed in 1990, which expired
on December 31, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The new document will define the juridical framework that will
guarantee the access of some 100 Venezuelan fishing ships to
exploit marine life resources in oceanic territories under
Suriname's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
It also re-activates the institutional mechanism set by the
Venezuela-Suriname Fishing Commission, which creates a permanent
contact between the fishing authorities of both countries.
</P>
<P>
"A satisfactory balance between the interests of both countries
is desirable, so that both countries will receive optimal social
and economic benefits from the sustainable exploitation and use of
resources from the sea," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Beyond the fishing operations of the Venezuelan ships, the
agreement also provides for greater cooperation in terms of marine
conservation, according to the Venezuela Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
