<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panamanian Government to Compensate U.S. Invasion Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian government
will pay 1.67 million U.S. dollars in compensation to families
affected by the U.S. invasion in 1989, according to a government
source.
</P>
<P>
The source said on Wednesday that 3,341 families that lost
family members and suffered material damages during the U.S.
bombing on the El Chorrillo neighborhood on the western outskirts
of the capital, will get compensated.
</P>
<P>
At midnight on December 20, 1989 U.S. troops mounted large-
scale attacks on Panamanian military targets aimed at toppling
General Manuel Antonio Noriega, who is now in jail in the U.S. on
drug-dealing charges.
</P>
<P>
During the combats, the El Chorrillo neighborhood, near
Noriega's former headquarters, was totally destroyed with hundreds
of people killed.
</P>
<P>
A human rights organization said the death toll well exceeded
1,000, but U.S. military authorities recognized only 300 victims,
military or civilian.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth compensation payment given by the Ernesto
Perez Balladares government.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the legislative commission on budget approved an
extraordinary credit in the order of 1.8 million dollars for the
government to pay for the compensation.
</P>
<P>
Before the end of his tenure, the Perez Balladares government
will pay last two other compensation quotas pledged to residents
of El Chorrillo, amounting to 3,500 dollars per affected
individual. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
