<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Still Facing Tough Financial Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations' tightened
financial situation has seen no improvement this year,
U.N. Under-Secretary-General Joseph Connor said in his report
released in Geneva on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The leading world body is expected to have a deficit of 247
million U.S. dollars in 1998, while the amount owed by its member
countries has hit 2.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the amount in arrears includes 683
million dollars for the daily budget, 1.8 billion dollars for
peace-keeping missions, and 22 million dollars for the use of the
International Court.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the U.N.'s largest debtor, owes 1.6 billion
dollars, about two thirds of the total amount in arrears, although
it already paid 228 million dollars to the U.N. this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
