<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Sign UN Human Rights Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will sign in the next
two months a key UN human rights agreement which guarantees
people's economic, social and cultural rights, according to a
government official.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from concerned government agencies and
non-governmental organizations recently completed scrutinizing the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights,
and it is now up to the cabinet to decide, Vasin Teeravechyan,
Head of the Foreign Ministry's Treaties and Legal Affairs
Department, was quoted Thursday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is expected to endorse the UN treaty before what is
internationally observed as Human Rights Day on December 10.
</P>
<P>
The International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural
Rights mainly guarantees Thai people's rights to freely choose
their work, receive fair wages with safe and health conditions and
equal opportunity for both sexes, as well as access to adequate
standard of living and education.
</P>
<P>
Thailand so far has ratified the three main UN human rights
agreements, namely the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights (1996), the Convention on the Rights of the Child
(1992), and the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of
Discrimination Against Women (1985). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
