<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Urges Leftists to Back Him in Budget Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
urged leftist allies to stop confronting the government over the
1999 draft budget, which he firmly defended before parliament on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Opening a Lower House debate set to end on Friday with a
confidence vote in the government, Prodi made an appeal to
hardline Secretary General of the Communist Refoundation party
Fausto Bertinotti to drop his rejection of the budget bill.
</P>
<P>
"This government was and is the one wanted by Communist
Refoundation voters," he said, "and I ask you, Bertinotti, in the
name of all those who voted for us, to turn back and reconsider."
</P>
<P>
The Communists, at their weekend meetings, voted to withhold
its vital support for the budget package, sparking concerns for
the survival of Prodi's 28-month administration, the only
left-leaning coalition in post-war Italy.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Bertinotti's choice was "incomprehensible" since he
was opposing a budget containing many measures to help the poor
and unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Communist deputies in the Lower House are sharply divided on
the issue. Party Chairman Armando Cossutta announced his
resignation on Monday in protest against Bertinotti's hardline
stance.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Communist Refoundation party, up
to 21 of the 34 Communist deputies are likely to join Cossutta in
support of Prodi in the confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
Prodi relies on the backing of the Communists to keep his
premiership. If he fails to win enough votes in parliament on
Friday, President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro could call new elections or
ask another leading figure to form a new majority and government.
</P>
</TEXT>
