<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Forced Landing to Be Shot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Last month's successful
emergency landing of a Chinese passenger plane at the Shanghai
Hongqiao Airport will be adapted into a movie.
</P>
<P>
"The production will be the first disaster movie made by
Chinese filmmakers," according to Director Zhang Jianya.
</P>
<P>
Today's Wenhui Daily reported that the Shanghai Film Studio
will produce the film which will be written by a scriptwriter from
the Beijing Film Academy.
</P>
<P>
The September 10 forced landing involved the No.1273 MD-11
aircraft operated by China Eastern Airlines. The plane departed
Hongqiao bound for Beijing at 19:38 in the evening, with pilots
discovering a landing gear problem shortly after takeoff.
</P>
<P>
The Hongqiao control tower granted approval for an emergency
landing. Two attempted touchdowns failed and the plane circled the
airport for three hours before running out of fuel and forcing the
emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
The plane was carrying 120 passengers and 17
crew. Miraculously, only 9 passengers suffered superficial
injuries.
</P>
<P>
The forced landing has been cited as one of the miracles in
aviation history worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, who is currently gathering background information at
Hongqiao, said the production will involve the extensive use of
visual effects and computer technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
