<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Drops From Top Causes of Deaths in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Death rate from AIDS dropped
by 47 percent in a year in the United States, indicating that
multidrug cocktails are effective in keeping the virus suppressed,
the U.S. government said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Center for Health Statistics reported that AIDS
dropped from the eighth most common cause of death in 1996 to the
14th in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Among people 25 to 44 years old, the group hardest hit by HIV
infection, AIDS dropped to the fifth-leading cause of death in
1997 from the leading cause in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Today's report is very good news for the nation, and the
tremendous decline in AIDS deaths is particularly striking," Donna
Shalala, secretary of health and human services, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"These figures mean that new treatments have been very
effective in extending the lives of people who already have HIV
infection, Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
However, "they do not mean we have significantly reduced HIV
transmission," she said. "Our ultimate goal is to prevent the
estimated 40,000 new HIV infections that occur each year."
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the infant mortality rate fell to 7.1
deaths per 1,000 live births from 7.2 deaths per 1,000 live births
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that last year, 864.9 people died for every
100,000 in the nation, down from 872.5 per 100,000 in 1996. Heart
disease and cancer are the top causes for deaths.
</P>
<P>
The statistics indicate that children born in 1997 can expect
to live 76.5 years, compared with 76.1 for children born in 1996,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
