<HEADLINE> Indonesian Press reports Military Personnel Involvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Military personnel and a
government official may have been involved in a mysterious murder
spree of more than 100 people in Indonesia's East Java province,
the Jakarta Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the leader of the provincial chapter of the
Nahdlatul Ulama (NU) Muslim organization Hasyim Muzadi as saying
that two members of the armed forces and a village chief were
suspects in the killings.
</P>
<P>
The alleged involvement of a village official was reported by
NU's investigation team, while the alleged involvement of the two
military personnel was explained by Regional Military Chief Maj.
Gen. Djoko Subroto on Saturday. Hasyim told about 100 NU
executives in the provincial capital of Surabaya on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-three victims have been confirmed in Bangyuwangi regency
since August. It was reported that in September, similar killings
took place on Madura, an island off East Java, where a number of
people had been killed. Eight people have been found dead in
similar circumstances in Jember regency recently.
</P>
<P>
Banyuwangi is a regency 280 kilometers east of Surabaya with a
population of 1.5 million people. The regency capital, Banyuwangi,
is a coastal town. Jember is about 105 kilometers west of
Bangyuwangi.
</P>
<P>
Banyuwangi and Jember are predominantly Muslim areas rooted in
the Nadhlatul Ulama (NU) tradition. NU is the country's largest
Muslim organization.
</P>
<P>
East Java Police chief Maj. Gen. M. Dayat has said he suspected
a mysterious murder spree in several towns was the result of an
"organized crime."
</P>
<P>
The police and the military are currently sheltering 277 people
who fear they may be targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
