<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Citizens Say Farewell To Popular Stove </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 8 (Xinhua) -- The "Tiger stove", which has
provided boiled water for the people of Shanghai's neighborhoods
for some 200 years, is gradually fading away.
</P>
<P>
The stove gets its name because of its bulky shape and a
chimney like a tiger's tail.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1900s, there were no thermoses available in
Shanghai, and people went to neighborhood shops to get boiled
water. But, even after thermoses began to appear, the shops were
still popular because most households used briquet stoves.
</P>
<P>
One used to be able to see a great number of these shops
scattered along the streets of the city, but most of them have
been demolished as households move into highrise apartment
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Hu Hongmei, who still runs one of these "tiger stove" shops,
says that people now use gas stoves and fewer of them come to her
shop for boiled water. The lack of customers is a major cause of
the disappearance of "tiger stoves". Hu says she makes about 20
yuan a day now and plans to close the business after some regular
customers living nearby move to a new apartment building next year.
</P>
<P>
A negative effect of the popular old stoves, according to a
Shanghai environmental protection department official, was that
they polluted the environment. The coal and wood that fueled them
used to pile up on the streets and produced an enormous amount of
dust, he explains.
</P>
<P>
The stoves also produce a large number of sulphur dioxide, the
official said, and said that removing them was one of the major
steps of the Municipal People's Government to reduce waste gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0280 </DOCNO>
