<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern China's "Green Great Wall" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, October 8 (Xinhua) -- Twenty years of afforestation in
northern China have begun to pay off as about five million
hectares of desert and wasteland become green again with
windbreaks and forest belts and four million hectares are covered
with forests that hold the water and soil.
</P>
<P>
One million hectares of farmland have begun to produce good
yields and another two million are pastureland.
</P>
<P>
The 'Northern, Northwestern, and Northeastern China Shelter
Forest Project' began in 1978 as the world's largest ecological
program, on a more than 10-million hectare area.
</P>
<P>
The Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region has benefited most because
about a third of the project involves the region, where drought
and strong winds keep trees from growing, forcing scientists to
apply more advanced afforestation technology.
</P>
<P>
The project has brought over 3.56 billion yuan worth of
forestry products and has helped to establish 60 factories for
processing these products.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to cover another one million hectares
of land by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0283 </DOCNO>
