<HEADLINE> Vieira Facing FA Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Arsenal midfielder Patrick
Vieira was charged with misconduct on Wednesday by the English
Football Association following their recent controversial game
with Sheffield Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The French international is alleged to have made gestures
towards the crowd following Wednesday's victory and been involved
in a separate incident in the players' tunnel.
</P>
<P>
Teammate Martin Keown has, however, escaped punishment after
being sent off in the same game in later September.
</P>
<P>
Keown and Wednesday's Paolo Di Canio were both given their
marching orders by referee Paul Alcock at Hillsborough after a
brawl broke out on the pitch.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old England defender appealed against his sending
off, saying that he had only been acting as a "peacemaker" and
had tried to prevent Di Canio from getting to Vieira.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally I am delighted with the outcome of the hearing. I
was greatly helped by the presence of David Dein, Arsene Wenger
and Gordon Taylor," said Keown.
</P>
<P>
"The FA investigated the matter very thoroughly and I would
like to thank them for the fairness they have displayed. I
believe they took my view that my intentions were that of a
peacemaker. Now I feel as if a weight has been lifted off my
shoulders."
</P>
<P>
Di Canio has been suspended by Wednesday for pushing Alcock to
the ground and will also face an FA misconduct charge but
Keown,backed by the Professional Footballers' Association and his
manager Arsene Wenger, has been told that "no further punishment"
would be imposed against him.
</P>
<P>
A FA statement said: "The commission accepted the view of
referee Paul Alcock that he had seen the arm of Martin Keown make
contact with Paolo Di Canio's face prior to both players being
sent off.
</P>
<P>
"The commission studied various video recordings of the
incident. They were not convinced Martin Keown had acted
deliberately. The sending off will stand, but the commission has
decided that no further punishment will be appropriate, " it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
