<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Net TVs to Edge Out PCs in American Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 7 (Xinhua) -- It has been the dream of
Bill Gates to have the PC on every desk in the United States, but
that's not going to happen, according to a new study released this
week.
</P>
<P>
Inteco, a U.S. market researcher focusing on consumers'
prosperity to adopt new technologies, said that the future of home
computing does not lie in expensive multimedia computers, but more
likely in some type of Internet TV.
</P>
<P>
Inteco's study shows that by 2003, set-top boxes will be able
to provide limited Internet access for a fraction of the cost of a
PC, leaving American consumers with less of a reason to invest in
a pricey desktop or notebook system.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of American households with PCs will grow
from 45.1 million in 1998 to 54.7 million in 2003, most of that
growth is derived from households with more than one computer, not
new users, according to Inteco.
</P>
<P>
The actual number of American households with PCs will only
grow from 44.8 million in 1998 to 52.7 million in 2003. This
presents a problem for the PC industry, Inteco said, because
dwindling prices and profit margins need to be offset by high
volumes.
</P>
<P>
About 30 percent of American households do not own a PC and
have no interest in purchasing a computer, the study found,
because they still see no crucial use for a home computer.
</P>
<P>
Part of the problem is that the PC industry has not yet
provided a compelling application for high-end PCs, said Inteco,
adding that "the PC industry can try and bring back the high-end
PC, but there isn't any new application that is driving the specs
higher."
</P>
<P>
Instead, limited local news, sports and weather information via
cable television or set-top box will likely captivate both PC and
non-PC households alike, Inteco said.
</P>
<P>
As many American households own more than one PC, home
computing could be stimulative for new chip making. Recent surveys
have shown that sharing Internet communications and printers are
two critical needs for home computer users in the United States.
To meet the needs, the Silicon Valley-based Lucent Technologies
has released a new chip family that will allowing home users to
share printers, files and Internet access. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
