<DOCNO> XIE19981008.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Says Its Economy Immune to Russia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Hungary's Prime Minister
Viktor Orban said Wednesday that Central Europe is no longer
economically tied to Moscow and is avoiding fallout from Russia's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We are very calm, relaxed and waiting for NATO memberships,"
Orban, 35, who took office in July said after meeting U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, meeting with Orban in the White House, said he does
not expect Hungary to be involved in military action in Kosovo
because "what is contemplated" is air strikes, not ground action.
</P>
<P>
Hungary hosts a major supply base for U.S.-led NATO military
peacekeeping operations in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Orban said Hungary, which is due to become a NATO member next
year, seeks a non-military end to violence in the Serb state, "but
if a decision is taken by NATO, we are ready to contribute as an
ally. We are ready to take part."
</P>
<P>
After meeting World Bank President James Wolfensohn, Orban said
the Russian crisis may provide a boon for Central Europe as a
secure haven for investments that might have gone to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
He said Hungary, Poland, the Czech Republic and Slovenia are
likely to grow at a faster rate than either Russia or the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
He said Hungary will pursue policies of predictability,
economic growth, balance and transparency.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing Russia, Orban said its real crisis is systemic rather
than either economic or social. He predicted a country without
effective government for years to come.
</P>
<P>
"That will be a major obstacle to aid," he said. "Without
government, it's unreasonable to give support."
</P>
<P>
He projected 5 percent growth for Hungary's economy this year,
adding that while this is a percentage point lower than expected,
it still is strong enough to demonstrate immunity to Russia's
problems.
</P>
<P>
Orban also projected reductions in the country's deficit, from
4.7 percent this year to 4 percent next year, and in inflation,
from 12 percent to less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Orban appealed to American and other potential investors in
Central Europe to separate Hungary, Poland, the Czech Republic and
Slovenia from other former Soviet satellites.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to restore favorable circumstances for
competition," he said. Hungary's success would become more obvious
in a year, Orban predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
