<HEADLINE> Asian Economic Crisis Cuts Immigration to Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of immigrants to
Canada is expected to drop by about 20,000 this year due to Asia's
severe economic crisis, the Canadian government said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Canada is expected to receive between 180,000 and 200,000
immigrants this year, less than the planned number of 200,000 to
225,000.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason the desired levels for 1998 were not reached
was the severe economic crisis in Asia," Minister of Citizenship
and Immigration Lucienne Robillard told the parliament while
tabling the country's 1999 immigration plan.
</P>
<P>
Most of Canada's immigrants in recent years have come from
Asia, she said. "But the current fiscal uncertainty and roller
coaster stock markets have caused many people to think twice about
plans to emigrate."
</P>
<P>
"This is well demonstrated in the fact that we had
approximately 15,000 visas wasted this year. That is 15,000 people
who were approved to come to Canada but decided at the last minute
not to," Robillard noted.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government is keeping the same forecast for 1999.
The desired levels of immigrants remain the same: between 200,000
and 225,000 people.
</P>
<P>
"Canada wants to make it very clear to the international
community that its doors are still just as wide open, despite a
difficult economic situation," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that we will see the Asian financial markets
stabilize and the immigration numbers rise again in the coming
year," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
