<HEADLINE> UK Central Bank Warns of Possible Euro Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England (BoE) has
warned the European Union against possible financial market
turmoil when the euro is launched next year, issuing a call on
central bankers across the 15-nation bloc to make contingency
plans.
</P>
<P>
In a report sent to the European Commission, the BoE noted that
the weekend of the euro's introduction, covering December 31 to
January 4, would be one of "greater than normal operational risk
for Europe's firms and financial infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented nature of forging a single currency among 11
European nations on January 1, 1999 meant the possibility of
insufficient preparations in the financial community to prevent
large-scale payment problems or speculation over the stability of
certain firms.
</P>
<P>
"If the final preparations for the introduction of the euro go
awry, central banks and regulators might have to manage a
potentially difficult situation," Reuters quoted the report as
saying.
</P>
<P>
As concern has intensified over the stability of leading
international banks, the report entitled "The Conversion Weekend:
What Could Go Wrong" cited risks for Europe's financial
institutions, highlighting four main areas of concern:
</P>
<P>
-- "Firms could experience shortages of liquidity because they
do not receive payments they expect, or cannot execute financing
transactions in securities, such as repos.
</P>
<P>
-- Payments and securities transactions fail to settle, which
could in turn cause further settlement failures as firms are left
short of cash or securities. This could lead to increasing or
unexpectedly prolonged exposure to settlement risk.
</P>
<P>
-- Firms are unable to trade, causing or prolonging exposure to
market movements. This would be significant in view of the
following point.
</P>
<P>
-- If the above problems become widespread, there could be
speculation, whether rational or not, for example over the future
of individual firms, or over the start of the EMU. This could
cause volatile and disorderly markets, including in the new euro
currency and FX markets."
</P>
<P>
The Bank's detailed warnings to the EU are similar to the
concerns expressed by major international banks in London, many of
whom believe that the euro's birth will be more difficult than is
generally perceived.
</P>
<P>
A group of 31 leading banks, called the Heathgrow Group, was
formed during the summer to tackle unresolved issues relating to
the euro's creation. The focus has been on payment and settlement
issues, with many warning there was insufficient coordination and
leadership in these critical areas.
</P>
<P>
For individual firms, the BoE said the potential risk of not
being able to trade because of systems failures could lead to
liquidity shortages, and if such a situation became severe, a loss
of confidence could arise among investors.
</P>
<P>
"Settlement risks could build up uncontrollably between
counterparties as chains of settlement failures developed...This
kind of situation could begin to threaten systemic stability if it
occurred at a number of firms at once," the Bank said.
</P>
<P>
For central bankers, the task was to ensure that they were well
prepared to manage such a crisis should it arise.
</P>
<P>
"The concentration of risk over this period means that each
individual central bank and regulator may wish to ensure they
would have the ability to cope with a serious problem at that
time," the Bank said. "The scope of the risk, covering as it does
the whole of Europe (and indeed elsewhere), means that regulators
and central banks may wish to plan how they would provide a swift,
decisive and co-ordinated response."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
