<HEADLINE> Romania, True Factor of Peace, Stability: Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 7 (Xinhua) -- Romania is a true factor of
peace and stability in the region, Leni Fischer, the visiting
president of the Council of Europe' Parliamentary Assembly, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Leni Fischer, who arrived in Bucharest Tuesday for a three-day
visit, made the remark in her speech at the festivity of the
Romanian Parliament, marking five years since the Balkan country
has been integrated with the Council of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"The Council of Europe's Parliamentary Assembly appreciates
appropriately Romania's efforts for keeping relations of good
neighborliness and cooperation with all the neighbors on the basis
of bilateral treaties and confidence measures," she said, adding
that she was attending the meeting "in order to encourage" Romania
to overcome the difficulties it was facing.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of
Europe said the monitoring procedure ceased last year as a result
of Romania's will and capability for striving for democracy, human
rights and pre-eminence in law.
</P>
<P>
Leni Fischer said that after a "full right integration" with
the Council of Europe five years ago, Romania got over the
necessary stages to win the confidence and respect of the members
of the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe.
</P>
<P>
Romania's democratic evolution in the last years, carefully
watched by the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe,
confirmed Romania's wish to strengthen the values promoted by the
Council of Europe and essential to the construction of today's
Europe, Leni Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
She said that the signing and ratification by Romania of the
most important legal instruments that had been worked out by the
Council of Europe, among which were the framework-Convention on
the protection of national minorities and the European Charter on
local autonomy, showed once again Romania's intention and
capability for actively participating in the construction of
tomorrow's Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
